{META_DATA}: "BIG FISH"
{META_DATA}: Written by
{META_DATA}: John August
{META_DATA}: Based on the novel by
{META_DATA}: Daniel Wallace
{META_DATA}: Final Production Draft
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is a Southern story, full of lies and fabrications, but truer for their inclusion.
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A RIVER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We're underwater, watching a fat catfish swim along.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is The Beast.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: There are some fish that cannot be caught.
{DIALOGUE}: It's not that they're faster or stronger than other fish.
{DIALOGUE}: They're just touched by something extra.
{DIALOGUE}: Call it luck.
{DIALOGUE}: Call it grace.
{DIALOGUE}: One such fish was The Beast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Beast's journey takes it past a dangling fish hook, baited with worms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Past a tempting lure, sparkling in the sun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Past a swiping bear claw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Beast isn't worried.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: By the time I was born, he was already a legend.
{DIALOGUE}: He'd taken more hundred- dollar lures than any fish in Alabama.
{DIALOGUE}: Some said that fish was the ghost of Henry Walls, a thief who'd drowned in that river 60 years before.
{DIALOGUE}: Others claimed he was a lesser dinosaur, left over from the Cretaceous period.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILL'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (1973)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WILL BLOOM, AGE 3, listens wide-eyed as his father EDWARD BLOOM, 40's and handsome, tells the story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In every gesture, Edward is bigger than life, describing each detail with absolute conviction.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't put any stock into such speculation or superstition.
{DIALOGUE}: All I knew was I'd been trying to catch that fish since I was a boy no bigger than you.
{META_DATA}: (closer)
{DIALOGUE}: And on the day you were born, that was the day I finally caught him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CAMPFIRE - NIGHT (1977)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A few years later, and Will sits with the other INDIAN GUIDES as Edward continues telling the story to the tribe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I'd tried everything on it: worms, lures, peanut butter, peanut butter-and-cheese.
{DIALOGUE}: But on that day I had a revelation: if that fish was the ghost of a thief, the usual bait wasn't going to work.
{DIALOGUE}: I would have to use something he truly desired.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward points to his wedding band, glinting in the firelight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LITTLE BRAVE
{META_DATA}: (confused)
{DIALOGUE}: Your finger?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward slips his ring off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Gold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While the other boys are rapt with attention, Will looks bored.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's heard this story before.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I tied my ring to the strongest line they made -- strong enough to hold up a bridge, they said, if just for a few minutes -- and I cast upriver.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM FRONT HALL - NIGHT (1987)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is chatting up Will's pretty DATE to the homecoming dance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is enjoying the story, but also the force of Edward's charisma.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's hypnotizing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: The Beast jumped up and grabbed it before the ring even hit the water.
{DIALOGUE}: And just as fast, he snapped clean through that line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WILL, now 17 with braces, is fuming and ready to leave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His mother SANDRA -- from whom he gets his good looks and practicality -- stands with him at the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You can see my predicament.
{DIALOGUE}: My wedding ring, the symbol of fidelity to my wife, soon to be the mother of my child, was now lost in the gut of an uncatchable fish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON WILL AND SANDRA
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (low but insistent)
{DIALOGUE}: Make him stop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His mother pats him sympathetically, then adjusts his tie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL'S DATE
{DIALOGUE}: What did you do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I followed that fish up-river and down-river for three days and three nights, until I finally had him boxed in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will regards his father with exasperated contempt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: With these two hands, I reached in and snatched that fish out of the river.
{DIALOGUE}: I looked him straight in the eye.
{DIALOGUE}: And I made a remarkable discovery.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TINY PARIS RESTAURANT (LA RUE 14°) - NIGHT (1998)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WILL, now 28, sits with his gorgeous bride JOSEPHINE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is their wedding reception, crowded with their friends and family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They should be joyful, but Will is furious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward has the floor, ostensibly for a toast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room is cozy and drunk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: This fish, the Beast.
{DIALOGUE}: The whole time we were calling it a him, when in fact it was a her.
{DIALOGUE}: It was fat with eggs, and was going to lay them any day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over near the doorway, we spot Sandra, just returned from the restrooms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks gorgeous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She couldn't be any happier if this were her own wedding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I was in a situation.
{DIALOGUE}: I could gut that fish and get my ring back, but doing so I would be killing the smartest catfish in the Ashton River, soon to be mother of a hundred others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will can't take any more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine tries to hold him back, but he gets up and leaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward doesn't even notice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Did I want to deprive my soon-to-be- born son the chance to catch a fish like this of his own?
{DIALOGUE}: This lady fish and I, well, we had the same destiny.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he leaves, Will mutters in perfect unison with his father --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD AND WILL
{DIALOGUE}: We were part of the same equation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will reaches the door, where his mother intercepts him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, it's still your night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will can't articulate his anger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He just leaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Now, you may well ask, since this lady fish wasn't the ghost of a thief, why did it strike so quick on gold when nothing else would attract it?
{META_DATA}: (closer; he holds up his ring)
{DIALOGUE}: That was the lesson I learned that day, the day my son was born.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He focuses his words on Sandra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This story is -- and has always been -- about her more than anyone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes, the only way to catch an uncatchable woman is to offer her a wedding ring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A LAUGH from the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward motions for Sandra to get up here with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she crosses, we can see that thirty years of marriage has not lessened their affection for each other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they kiss, Edward tweaks her chin a special little way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd APPLAUDS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward toasts the happy couple.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine covers well for her absent husband, a smile as warm as summer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward downs his champagne in a gulp.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OUTSIDE LA RUE 14° - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We come into the middle of an argument on the sidewalk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Occasional PASSERSBY take notice, especially as it gets more heated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both men are a little drunk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What, a father's not allowed to talk about his son?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (disbelieving)
{DIALOGUE}: I am a footnote in that story.
{DIALOGUE}: I am the context for your great adventure.
{DIALOGUE}: Which never happened!
{DIALOGUE}: Incidentally!
{DIALOGUE}: You were selling novelty products in Wichita the day I was born.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (shaking his head)
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus Christ.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Friend of yours?
{DIALOGUE}: Did you help him out of a bind?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, Will.
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone likes that story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: No Dad, they don't.
{DIALOGUE}: I do not like the story.
{DIALOGUE}: Not anymore, not after a thousand times.
{DIALOGUE}: I know all the punchlines, Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: I can tell them as well as you can.
{META_DATA}: (closer)
{DIALOGUE}: For one night, one night in your entire life, the universe does not revolve around Edward Bloom.
{DIALOGUE}: It revolves around me and my wife.
{DIALOGUE}: How can you not understand that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat, then...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (low)
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry to embarrass you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will won't let him get the last word.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You're embarrassing yourself, Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: You just don't see it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A hand to wave, enough of you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Will, still fuming with righteous anger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's then we FREEZE FRAME.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: After that night, I didn't speak to my father again for three years.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. A.P. NEWSROOM (PARIS) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A typically busy day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On hold with the phone cradled under an ear, Will sorts through a bundle of mail dropped on his desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (ON PHONE)
{META_DATA}: (without pauses)
{DIALOGUE}: William Bloom with the Associated Press if I could just...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's put back on hold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Returning to the mail, he finds a hand-addressed envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rips it open.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: We communicated indirectly I guess.
{DIALOGUE}: In her letters and Christmas cards, my mother would write for both of them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE KITCHEN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the table, Sandra talks on the phone while Edward fixes a sandwich.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When I'd call, Mom would say that Dad was out driving.
{DIALOGUE}: Or swimming in the pool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward takes a seat, starting to eat his sandwich.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: True to form, we never talked about our not talking.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE MASTER BEDROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra stands by the window, watching as...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BLOOM BACK YARD - NIGHT [CONTINUOUS]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward swims laps in the family pool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's born to the water.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The truth is, I didn't see anything of myself in my father, and I don't think he saw anything of himself in me.
{DIALOGUE}: We were like strangers who knew each other very well.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward stares intently into the water, a lion in wait.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In telling the story of my father's life, it's impossible to separate the fact from the fiction, the man from the myth.
{DIALOGUE}: The best I can do is to tell it the way he told me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LOOK DOWN at the river, where Edward's reflection is caught in the dark water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the water ripples past, something changes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sure enough, as we LOOK UP again, it's a younger EDWARD BLOOM, 20's, staring into the water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's not just handsome, not just charming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's as if all the forces of the natural world had conspired to create him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It doesn't always make sense, and most of it never happened.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, this Edward thrusts both hands into the water, grabbing hold of
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE BEAST.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He brings the catfish up to his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looks it right in the eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then the Beast spits out Edward's gold ring.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But that's what kind of story this is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Smiling, Edward takes the ring, then throws the Beast back into the water with a splash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TITLE OVER:
{META_DATA}: BIG FISH
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Dr. Bennett stands between the Wife's legs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's flustered and sweating, but the doctor has a comforting bedside manner...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Now, Mrs. Bloom, I'll need you to give me one good push.
{DIALOGUE}: On three.
{DIALOGUE}: One...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, we hear a POP as a slimy mass of human being rockets into the doctor's unprepared hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bennett tries to hold tight, but the infant is slippery like a fish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It shoots up into air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The NURSES and the Husband try to grab the baby, but no one can hold it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the newborn sails upward TOWARDS CAMERA, we can see a GIGGLING SMILE on its face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As it falls, the newborn knocks over a tray, which provides it a ramp to slide right out of the room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone races after it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bursting through the doors --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Grab that baby!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A NURSE finally scoops up the slippery baby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone lets out a collective sigh of relief.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: My father's birth would set the pace for his unlikely life.
{DIALOGUE}: No longer than most men's, but larger.
{DIALOGUE}: And as strange as his stories got, the endings were always the most surprising of all.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALF-DARK PARIS APARTMENT - (PRESENT) DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over the sound of rain, a phone RINGS on a chair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By the tone of the ring, we know we're not in the U.S. -- it has that insistent European sound.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As it keeps RINGING, we look to see the apartment is mostly empty, just a few half-unpacked boxes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cradle is still in its carton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: KEYS in the lock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LAUGHTER in the hallway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door swings open to reveal a drenched Will (29) carrying four sacks of groceries, the bottoms collapsing from the rain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His wife Josephine (28) pushes past him to get the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Allo oui?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will begins stripping out of his wet clothes, each layer unleashing a new drizzle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He plays it up, trying to get a reaction out of Josephine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, he's here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands the phone to Will, concerned.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: It's your mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Half-stripped, Will takes the phone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This won't be good news.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Josephine takes off her rain coat, we see she is very, very pregnant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She listens carefully to Will's side of the conversation, trying to gauge how bad the news is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: What does Dr. Bennett say?
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: No, sure, let me talk to him.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll wait.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He covers the mouthpiece.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looks over to Josephine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: It's bad.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: It's more than they thought.
{DIALOGUE}: They're going to stop chemo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: You need to go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Probably tonight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going with you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have to.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (a simple fact)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going with you.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AIR FRANCE 747 - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the plane continues boarding, a STEWARDESS recites the welcome spiel in French.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will has a window seat in coach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine sits beside him, putting on hand lotion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Taking his hands, she rubs the excess into him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's an effortless intimacy between them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She can pinpoint what he's feeling before he can.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. 747 / FLYING - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hours later, and the lights are dimmed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Most of the PASSENGERS are asleep, including Josephine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her head is propped against Will's shoulder, her hands tucked under her belly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will watches her sleep, brushing back her hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then he notices a BORED BOY in the next row over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Off the glow of the reading light, the boy is using his hands to cast shadows on the seat back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid is pretty good, making a convincing bird, a passable monkey, and finally a dog.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PUSH IN on the silhouettes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (O.S., PRELAP)
{DIALOGUE}: So which one's it gonna be?
{DIALOGUE}: The Monkey in the Barn, the Dog in the Road?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Focusing on the final shadow, we...
{META_DATA}: MATCH CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...come to find Edward making the shapes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will (6) sits in his pajamas on the floor next to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The endtable lamp lies between them, its shade off to cast big shadows on the wall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: The one about the witch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Your mom says I can't tell you that one anymore.
{DIALOGUE}: You get nightmares.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not scared.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks around for a beat, seeing if his wife is in earshot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He then leans in, complicitous.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Neither was I.
{DIALOGUE}: At first.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will smiles, excited to hear the forbidden story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: This all happened in the swamp outside of Ashton.
{DIALOGUE}: Kids weren't supposed to go out in the swamp, on account of the snakes and spiders and quicksand that would swallow you up before you could even scream.
{DIALOGUE}: But there were five of us out there that night: Me, Ruthie, Wilbur Freely, and the Price Brothers, Don and Zacky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward holds up his hand, counting the names on his fingers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Not a one of us knew what was in store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As his hand moves past the light, we
{META_DATA}: COME TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A flashlight SWEEPS past.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD AT THE SWAMP EDGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The night is WHIRRING and BREATHING, alive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The moon hangs low, casting long shadows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Five kids walk past in silhouette.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Four have flashlights on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The fifth keeps tripping, crashing into YOUNG EDWARD (10).
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Zacky, turn your flashlight on!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACKY
{DIALOGUE}: I don't got any batteries!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Red-headed ZACKY PRICE is 10.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His brother DON PRICE is 12, and a lot bigger than the others.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Then why'd you bring it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACKY
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to be in the swamp with a witch and no flashlight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WILBUR FREELY, also 10, is the black asthmatic son of a sharecropper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Redheaded RUTHIE MACKLIN, 8, is happy just to be there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Is it true she got a glass eye?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILBUR FREELY
{DIALOGUE}: I heard she got it from Gypsies.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What's a Gypsy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACKY
{DIALOGUE}: Your momma's a Gypsy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Your momma's a bitch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTHIE
{DIALOGUE}: You shouldn't swear.
{DIALOGUE}: There's ladies present.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Shit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACKY
{DIALOGUE}: Damn.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILBUR FREELY
{DIALOGUE}: Screw.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (whispering)
{DIALOGUE}: Turn off your flashlights!
{DIALOGUE}: She'll see 'em.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MOVING UP behind the kids, we find ourselves at the gates of...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. A CREEPY OLD HOUSE - NIGHT
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADULT EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, it's common knowledge that most towns of a certain size have a witch, if only to eat misbehaving children and the occasional puppy who wanders into her yard.
{DIALOGUE}: Witches use those bones to cast spells and curses that make the land infertile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PULL BACK, and BACK, revealing more of the Gothically creepy house: its broken windows, strangling vines, and eerie gargoyles half-buried in the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even bats are afraid to fly over it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the moonlight, the house is especially sinister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Who knows what is lurking in the shadows?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADULT EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Yet of the all the witches in Alabama, there was one who was the most feared.
{DIALOGUE}: For she had one glass eye, which was said to contain mystical powers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We finally come to the kids, staring in through the gate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILBUR FREELY
{DIALOGUE}: I hear if you look right at it, you can see how you're gonna die.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That's bull-s-h-i-t, that is.
{DIALOGUE}: She's not even a real witch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: You're so sure, why don't you go in and get that eye?
{DIALOGUE}: I heard she keeps it in a box on her nighttable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks back at the spooky house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Or are you too scared?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'll go in right now and get that eye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Then do it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Fine, I will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Fine, you do it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Fine, I'm doing it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands Zacky his flashlight, then starts climbing the gate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUTHIE
{DIALOGUE}: Edward, don't!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILBUR FREELY
{DIALOGUE}: She'll make soap out of you!
{META_DATA}: (to Ruthie)
{DIALOGUE}: That's what she does, she makes soap out of people.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward drops down on the far side of the gate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Truth be told, Edward is scared, but he forges ahead anyway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wilbur looks to Ruthie, and they're in complete agreement.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They get the hell out of there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Zacky would run too, but Don holds him by the collar.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. APPROACHING THE HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward curves around the tall bushes that hide the front door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anything could jump out of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He steps on the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The boards SQUEAL and CREAK, but he continues on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cat SCREAMS OUT from a broken wicker rocker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Catching his breath, Edward reaches the front door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The doorknob is ancient brass, two projections that look like horns.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Yet Edward extends his hand, reaching closer and closer before he finally
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RINGS THE DOORBELL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Impossibly fast, the door opens, revealing an OLD WOMAN with a patch over her left eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks like she's been dead for years, but too stubborn to lie down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (calm and straightforward)
{DIALOGUE}: Ma'am, my name is Edward Bloom, and there's some folks'd like to see your eye.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BACK AT THE GATE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Zacky and Don Price wait for Edward, each moment more convinced he's already dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But suddenly, he's back at the gate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: You get the eye?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I brought it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{META_DATA}: (dubious)
{DIALOGUE}: Let's see it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman steps out of the shadows behind Edward, flipping up her eye patch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When their flashlight beam hits her left eye, it shines with a hellish glow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We RUSH IN on Zacky, who is paralyzed by what he sees.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FRONT PORCH OF HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An OLD MAN -- Zacky -- stands on a wobbly stepladder, changing a lightbulb.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, the ladder gives way and he falls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dead.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AT THE GATE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We RUSH IN on Don Price.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FRATERNITY HOUSE BATHROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Twenty-year old Don Price falls face-forward on the tile, face mushed in the grout.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Very much dead.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AT THE GATE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don and Zacky both tremble with fear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The latter has tears in his eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACKY
{DIALOGUE}: I saw how I was gonna die.
{DIALOGUE}: I was old, and I fell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: I wasn't old at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The brothers suddenly bolt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still standing next to the Old Woman, Edward smiles.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AT THE OLD WOMAN'S DOOR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward helps her back inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He could leave now, but curiosity gets the better of him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I was thinking about death and all.
{DIALOGUE}: About seeing how you're gonna die.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman turns to him slightly, still not facing him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, on one hand, if dying was all you thought about, it could kind of screw you up.
{DIALOGUE}: But it could kind of help you, couldn't it?
{DIALOGUE}: Because you'd know that everything else you can survive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman smiles a little, a crooked grin of broken teeth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I guess I'm saying, I'd like to know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman turns leaning her face right in front of his.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And on a silent count of one, two, three -- Edward looks into The Eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This time we don't cut.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Instead, we HOLD ON Edward as he witnesses his death.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stares transfixed, perplexed and amused.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever he sees, it's not as dire as the other boys.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His future has something strange in store.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Huh.
{DIALOGUE}: That's how I go?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still a little overwhelmed, Edward turns and leaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ADULT EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: From that moment on, I no longer feared death.
{DIALOGUE}: And for that, I was as good as immortal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Edward leaves, the door swings SHUT on its own.
{META_DATA}: MATCH CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT./EXT. BLOOM HOUSE - (PRESENT) DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The front door opens to reveal Will and Josephine on the porch with their bags.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: REVERSE to Will's mother Sandra (53), surprised and a little annoyed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: How did you get here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: We swam.
{DIALOGUE}: The Atlantic, it's not that big really.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Ruth McHibbon offered to pick you up at the airport.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: We rented a car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (simply)
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't need to do that.
{DIALOGUE}: You just didn't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Starting over...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, Mom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans in and hugs her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She surrenders, squeezing her son tight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will and his mother are cut from the same cloth -- strong-willed but practical.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They've always been close.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I'm so glad you're here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That hug finished, Sandra pushes past her son to her daughter- in-law.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seeing the size of her belly --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: You shouldn't have flown.
{DIALOGUE}: But...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They hug.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: It's good to see you.
{DIALOGUE}: You look beautiful.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not flattery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the truth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll bet you need to --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Down the hall on the right.
{DIALOGUE}: The door sticks.
{DIALOGUE}: You have to really pull it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine squeezes past, a smile to her husband -- be nice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will heads back to the rental car to retrieve luggage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra follows him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coming down the driveway, we get to see the house for the first time: an older suburban home, three bedrooms, big for the neighborhood, and nicely grown into the lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: KIDS are playing on the street.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Is that Dr. Bennett's car?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: He's up with your father.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Heading back to the house...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How is he?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: He's impossible.
{DIALOGUE}: He won't eat.
{DIALOGUE}: And because he won't eat, he gets weaker.
{DIALOGUE}: And because he's weaker, he doesn't want to eat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How much time does he have left?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: You don't talk about those things.
{DIALOGUE}: Not yet.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. KITCHEN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra is pouring iced tea for Will and Josephine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DR. JULIUS BENNETT (85) enters from the foyer, still winded from coming down the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He was the town's first Black physician.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's still the town's best physician.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dr. Bennett.
{DIALOGUE}: It's good to see you.
{META_DATA}: (they shake)
{DIALOGUE}: My wife, Josephine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: A pleasure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He judges her belly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: You're seven months.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (impressed)
{DIALOGUE}: To the day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans close to her, whispering in her ear...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: It's a boy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smiles, surprised but not doubting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will looks over -- what did he say?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine shakes her head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Back to the main subject...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: You don't think he looks any worse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I would say he's the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And in the silence that follows, a lot is said.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It wasn't the upbeat reply Sandra was hoping for.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Can I see him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Absolutely.
{DIALOGUE}: Be good for you to talk to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A moment of awkwardness -- everyone here knows they haven't spoken in years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra hands Will a squat can of Ensure from the case on the counter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Get him to drink one of these.
{DIALOGUE}: He won't, but tell him he has to.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FOYER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coming out from the kitchen, Will slowly climbs the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They CREAK with every step.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The wall is filled with family photos, happier times.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Most of the pictures are of Will, starting when he was an infant and ending at his wedding.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he climbs the stairs, we can see him growing up with every step.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPSTAIRS HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A crack of sunlight spills around the half-open door at the end of the hallway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will walks towards it, running a hand along the wallpaper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost at the door, he stops for a beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gets his breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then goes inside.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward Bloom, 61, lies asleep on the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Although he's not the vibrant man we've seen before, it's not as bad we feared.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The illness has been quick, and left him largely intact.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are no I.V.'s, no monitors, nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coming up to the bed --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward cracks open an eye, a beat before he focuses.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to say something, but no words come out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks over at a pitcher on the nightstand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will pours him a glass of water, helping him hold it to his parched lips.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finished, Edward sets down the glass by himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A very long, tense beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will almost speaks again to fill the silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You --
{META_DATA}: (he points)
{DIALOGUE}: -- are in for a surprise.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Am I?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Having a kid changes everything.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, there's the diapers and the burping and the midnight feedings...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Did you do any of that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No, but I hear it's terrible.
{DIALOGUE}: Then you spend years trying to corrupt and mislead this child, fill its head with nonsense and still it turns out perfectly fine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You think I'm up for it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You learned from the best.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will doesn't rise to the challenge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then he remembers the can of Ensure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holds it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward recoils.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Just drink half the can.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll tell her you drank the whole thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone wins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then Edward rolls his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will cracks open the can, finding a straw on the nightstand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: People needn't worry so much.
{DIALOGUE}: It's not my time yet.
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't how I go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Really.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Truly.
{DIALOGUE}: I saw it in The Eye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: The Old Lady by the swamp.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: She was a witch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: No, she was old and probably senile.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe schizophrenic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I saw my death in that eye.
{DIALOGUE}: And this is not how it happens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: So how does it happen?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Surprise ending.
{DIALOGUE}: Wouldn't want to ruin it for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward slurps down as much of the Ensure as he can stand, then pushes the can away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swallows with difficulty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: There was this panhandler who used to stop me every morning when I came out of this coffee shop near the office.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: And every day I gave him a quarter.
{DIALOGUE}: Every day.
{DIALOGUE}: Then I got sick and was out for a couple of weeks.
{DIALOGUE}: And when I went back there, you know what he said?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What did he say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You owe me three-fifty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Really.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: True story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: When did you ever work in an office?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: There's a lot you don't know about me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You're right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward gives a wry smile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walked into that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother was worried we wouldn't talk again.
{DIALOGUE}: And look at us.
{DIALOGUE}: We're talking fine.
{DIALOGUE}: We're storytellers, both of us.
{DIALOGUE}: I speak mine out, you write yours down.
{DIALOGUE}: Same thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will won't commit to Edward's assessment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, I'm hoping we can talk about some things while I'm here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You mean, while I'm here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I'd just like to know the true versions of things.
{DIALOGUE}: Events.
{DIALOGUE}: Stories.
{DIALOGUE}: You.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward LAUGHS a little, which becomes a COUGH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The HACKING escalates until another drink of water gets it under control.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not clear whether any of this was an act to keep from talking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother hasn't been keeping up the pool.
{DIALOGUE}: If you wanted to you could...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You know where the chemicals are?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I used to do it when you were gone, remember?
{DIALOGUE}: I used to do it a lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He didn't mean for that to sound so pointed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Taking the half- empty Ensure, Will gets up to go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's at the door when...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I was never much for being at home, Will.
{DIALOGUE}: It's too confining.
{DIALOGUE}: And this, here.
{DIALOGUE}: Being stuck in bed.
{DIALOGUE}: Dying is the worst thing that ever happened to me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles at his joke.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you weren't dying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I said this isn't how I go.
{DIALOGUE}: The last part is much more unusual.
{DIALOGUE}: Trust me on that.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPSTAIRS HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shutting the door behind himself, Will drinks the rest of the Ensure himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward was right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It tastes horrible.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Heading for the stairs, Will walks past an open door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he leaves frame, we STAY BEHIND to look inside...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILL'S BEDROOM - DAY [FLASHBACK]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...where an eight-year old Will is propped up in bed, his face covered with chicken pox and pink calamine lotion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's showing Edward how many bumps there are on his arm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dr. Bennett says I'm going to have to be home for a week.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That's nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: I once had to stay in bed for three years.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Did you have chicken pox?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I wish.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TINY CHURCH - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wearing a white shirt and tie, YOUNG EDWARD -- still about 10 -- sings "Down to the River My Lord" along with the CONGREGATION.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His voice is high and thin, but he gives it his all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, his voice CRACKS and DROPS a half-octave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then another.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His friends Wilbur Freeley and Ruthie look over, wondering what's wrong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Embarrassed, Edward just keeps SINGING, trying to follow along with the baritone part.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls at his collar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then pulls again, his face getting red.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Starting to panic, he loosens his tie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's starting to undo the collar button when it POPS off by itself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two more buttons fly off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One hits a CHUBBY WOMAN in the neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON HIS SHOES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we watch, Edward's pant cuffs rise inch by inch -- that's how fast he's growing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Truth is, no one quite knew what was wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: Most times, a person grows up gradually.
{DIALOGUE}: I found myself in a hurry.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. YOUNG EDWARD'S BEDROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Edward lies in bed, his limbs connected to various pulleys and levers to support his weight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has a dozen encyclopedias around him, and another dozen on the floor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: My muscles couldn't keep up with my bones, and my bones couldn't keep up with my body's ambition.
{DIALOGUE}: So I spent the better part of three years confined to my bed, with the World Book Encyclopedia being my only means of exploration.
{DIALOGUE}: I had made it all the way to the "G's," hoping to find an answer to my gigantificationism, when I uncovered an article about the common goldfish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT: The encyclopedia article, complete with drawings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (reading)
{DIALOGUE}: "Kept in a small bowl, the goldfish will remain small.
{DIALOGUE}: With more space, the fish can grow double, triple, or quadruple its size."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Edward thinks this through.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It occurred to me then, that perhaps the reason for my growth was that I was intended for larger things.
{DIALOGUE}: After all, a giant man can't have an ordinary-sized life.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BASEBALL FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The CRACK of a bat announces the game-winning home run.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd CHEERS the swing, and especially the batter as he rounds the bases.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Although we've seen him briefly before, this is our first real exposure to GROWN-UP EDWARD, who we'll follow from roughly the ages of 18 to 30.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As soon as my bones had settled in their adult configuration, I set upon my plan to make a bigger place for myself in Ashton.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SCHOOL FIELDS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SINGLE SHOTS: Football hero Edward leads his team to victory.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the sidelines, a PRETTY GIRL admits the name of her secret love:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GIRL
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other GIRLS SQUEAL in agreement.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don Price looks over, glowers.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NEIGHBORHOOD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SINGLE SHOT: A lawnmower ROARS along the grass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LOOK UP to see who's pushing it, but it's not Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's one of his teenage EMPLOYEES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is back at the truck, which is painted to read, "Bloom Landscaping."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has workers on every lawn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He signs an autograph for an ADMIRING CUB SCOUT.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BASKETBALL COURT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward takes an impossible shot at the buzzer from the other end of the court.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Naturally, he makes it, winning the game.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the crowd goes wild for Edward, Don Price is the only teammate who doesn't mob him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TOWN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward carries a dog out of a burning house.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SCIENCE FAIR - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward wins a blue ribbon for his invention, a machine labelled "Perpetual Motion."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He and the JUDGE pose for a photograph.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A FLASH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pissed, Don Price throws his crappy lima bean plants in the trash.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HIGH SCHOOL STAGE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dashingly handsome Edward leads the CAST out for a curtain call.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's the star of the show.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Off to the side, we see Don Price is the ass-end of a horse costume.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward soaks in his applause, smiling and gracious.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GRADUATION STAGE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward accepts his diploma.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The PRINCIPAL hugs him tight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I was the biggest thing Ashton had ever seen.
{DIALOGUE}: Until one day, a stranger arrived.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FARM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As two FARMERS shake their heads, we REVERSE to a show a massive hole punched through the side of a barn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's roughly the shape of man, but no human could be that large.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SHEEP PEN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two fat ewes look up, a shadow falling across them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They BLEAT in panic as
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TWO OVERSIZED HANDS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: reach in and scoop them up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their protests continue as they're carried away, one under each arm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We still haven't seen the full stranger.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COURT HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MOB of about 50 have gathered, many of them with shotguns.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amid the crowd we see Don Price.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHARECROPPER
{DIALOGUE}: He ate an entire cornfield!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LITTLE GIRL
{DIALOGUE}: He ate my dog!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HOT-BLOODED SHOTGUN TOTER
{DIALOGUE}: If you ain't gonna stop him Mayor, we will!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{DIALOGUE}: I won't have mob violence in this town.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, has someone tried talking to him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOME FARMER
{DIALOGUE}: You can't reason with 'im!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHEPHARD
{DIALOGUE}: He's a monster!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Agreement from the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll do it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone turns to see who said that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd parts to reveal none other than Edward Bloom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don Price glowers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'll talk to him.
{DIALOGUE}: See if I can get him to move on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{DIALOGUE}: Son, that creature could crush you without trying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Trust me, he'll have to try.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HILL OUTSIDE ASHTON - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward climbs up the last bit of the steep hillside, reaching the mouth of a cave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Outside, buzzards squabble over the remains of the giant's feast: broken barrels, bones picked clean.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In his most serious voice, Edward calls out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Hello!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's no answer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: My name is Edward Bloom!
{DIALOGUE}: I want to talk to you!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From deep in a cave, a thunderous voice:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: GO AWAY!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The giant's voice has such force, it blows Edward's hair back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not going anywhere until you show yourself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then we hear a RUMBLE, like a train coming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward braces himself, fists ready for a fight, if that's what it's going to take.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the RUMBLE gets louder, the ground starts to shake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even Edward starts to worry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just how big is this guy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Armed with the foreknowledge of my own death, I knew the giant couldn't kill me.
{DIALOGUE}: All the same, I preferred to keep my bones unbroken.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward picks up a stone, ready to play David to Goliath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then suddenly, the giant bursts forth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hunched over, he slams into a stunned Edward, knocking him halfway down the hill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: KARL THE GIANT is bigger than any man you've ever seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not just tall, but massive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's completely feral, with a beard to his elbow and skin scratched and blistered.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What remains of his clothes are ragged and muddy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: God knows what's living in his matted hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl leans over Edward, blocking the sun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward throws his rock, but it just bounces off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The giant didn't even notice it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: Why are you here?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward ponders the best response, settling on...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: So you can eat me.
{DIALOGUE}: The town decided to send a human sacrifice, and I volunteered.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl's eyes narrow, confused.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward stands up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: My arms are a little stringy, but there's some good eating on my legs.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, I'd be tempted to eat them myself.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: So I guess, just, if you could get it over with quick.
{DIALOGUE}: Because I'm not much for pain, really.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward closes his eyes, hands at his side, ready to be eaten.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl just stares at him, not sure what to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a beat, Edward opens his eyes a tiny bit, just to see what the giant is doing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Relieved to see he's not licking his chops --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I can't go back.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a human sacrifice.
{DIALOGUE}: If I go back, everyone will think I'm a coward.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'd rather be dinner than a coward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl sits down with a BOOM, dejected.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Here, start with my hand.
{DIALOGUE}: It'll be an appetizer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching up, Edward shoves his hand into Karl's mouth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the giant spits it back out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to eat you.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to eat anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: It's just I get so hungry.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm too big.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And that's the sad truth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl is less a monster than a freak -- a giant man, but in the end, just a man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward takes a seat beside him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Did you ever think maybe you're not too big?
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe this town's just too small.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, look at it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Circling behind them, we look down at Ashton -- a tiny town in a tiny valley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Hardly two stories in the whole place.
{DIALOGUE}: Now I've heard in real cities, they've got buildings so tall you can't even see the tops of 'em.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: Really?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Wouldn't lie to you.
{DIALOGUE}: And they've got all-you-can-eat buffets.
{DIALOGUE}: You can eat a lot, can't you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: I can.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: So why are you wasting your time in a small town?
{DIALOGUE}: You're a big man.
{DIALOGUE}: You should be in the big city.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl smiles, but then it fades.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A certain sad suspicion --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: You're just trying to get me to leave, aren't you?
{DIALOGUE}: That's why they sent you here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What's your name, Giant?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: Karl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Mine's Edward.
{DIALOGUE}: And truthfully, I do want you to leave, Karl.
{DIALOGUE}: But I want to leave with you.
{META_DATA}: (closer)
{DIALOGUE}: You think this town is too small for you, well, it's too small for a man of my ambition.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't see staying here a day longer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: You don't like it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I love every square inch of it.
{DIALOGUE}: But I can feel the edges closing in on me.
{DIALOGUE}: A man's life can only grow to a certain size in a place like this.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: So what do you say?
{DIALOGUE}: Join me?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl thinks a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They shake on it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Now first, we gotta get you ready for the city.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN A SINGLE SHOT, Karl cuts his hair with hedge clippers, while Edward cuts up a surplus army tent to make him a shirt.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET OF ASHTON - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spirits buoyed by the high school MARCHING BAND, all the good CITIZENS of Ashton are gathered to see off Edward and Karl.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a few tears amid the familiar faces.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{META_DATA}: (loudly, for the crowd)
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom, first son of Ashton, it's with a heavy heart we see you go.
{DIALOGUE}: But take with you this Key to the City, and know that any time you want to come back, all our doors are open to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward ducks a bit so the Mayor can put the key around his neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd CHEERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that, Edward and Karl start walking, waving as they go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only DON PRICE, smoking on the corner, isn't sad to see Edward go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He crushes his cigarette under his heel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wishes he could crush Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Many of the townfolk come onto the street to hug Edward or shake his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: That afternoon as I left Ashton, everyone seemed to have advice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VARIOUS TOWNFOLK
{DIALOGUE}: Find yourself a nice girl!
{DIALOGUE}: Don't trust anyone in Kentucky!
{DIALOGUE}: Watch your pride, Edward Bloom!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But there was one person whose counsel I held above all others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the crowd parts, he finds himself face to face with
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE OLD WOMAN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The ruckus slows and quiets, as if a strange spell has been cast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She motions for Edward to lean down, so she can whisper something to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Although we're VERY CLOSE, we can't hear her voice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: She said that the biggest fish in the river gets that way by never being caught.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The advice only succeeds in confusing Edward.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (to the Old Woman)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward and Karl keep walking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Old Woman shuffles off, somehow knowing her advice will go unheeded.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: What did she say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Beats me.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We TILT UP from the road to reveal Edward and Karl walking out of Ashton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Each wears a backpack with all his earthly possessions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: There were two roads out of Ashton, a new one which was paved, and an older one that wasn't.
{DIALOGUE}: People didn't use the old road anymore, and it had developed the reputation of being haunted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward and Karl come to a bend, where the paved road veers left and an overgrown dirt road runs straight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The old road is blocked with signs and warnings of danger.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Since I had no intention of ever returning to Ashton, this seemed as good a time as any to find out what lay down that old road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl looks at the dirt road, wary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: You know anyone's who's taken it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That poet, Norther Winslow did.
{DIALOGUE}: He was going to Paris, France.
{DIALOGUE}: He must have liked it, because no one ever heard from him again.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Tell you what.
{DIALOGUE}: You take the other way and I'll cut through here.
{DIALOGUE}: Meet you on the far side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little paranoid...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: You're not trying to run away?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Just to be sure, you can take my pack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl perks up, even though it means more for him to carry.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. DIRT ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The road is overgrown, but not altogether creepy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is still shining, and the birds still CHIRPING.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spinning the Key to the City, Edward WHISTLES, because it's a day meant for whistling.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FURTHER ALONG - ROUGH PATH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The road has narrowed to a rough path.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spikes of sunlight break through the thick canopy, catching particles in the air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, Edward WHISTLES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coming around a bend, his PITCH DROPS as he sees thick, thorny vines growing across the path.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For the first time, he realizes the birds have stopped singing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The forest is dead quiet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks back the way he came.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's tempting to go back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It would be easier to go back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Edward presses on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He carefully steps through the thorns.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His trouser legs catch on the barbs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can hear the fabric TEAR.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FURTHER ALONG
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A scratched and sweaty Edward waves off various STINGING BUGS flying at him, finally whipping off his hat to swat at them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just then a CAWING crow swoops down and grabs the hat right out of his hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You stupid sonofa...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops his swearing, but grabs a rock and throws it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The stone ricochets off a tree and into a BEE'S NEST.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The swarm roars out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward high-tails it, each step still precarious.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE DARK FOREST - DAY [LATER]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is bruised, battered and bee-stung.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A half-broken sign lies in the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward picks it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reads it:
{META_DATA}: WARNING!
{META_DATA}: JUMPING SPIDERS!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sure enough, up ahead he sees the path is overgrown with thick cobwebs, heavy from the rain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: There comes a point where a reasonable man will swallow his pride and admit he's made a terrible mistake.
{DIALOGUE}: The truth is, I was never a reasonable man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward tosses the sign and forges ahead, into the spiderwebs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: And what I recalled of Sunday School was that the more difficult something became, the more rewarding it was in the end.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CLEARING / THE ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward emerges from the forest, brushing the last cobwebs off and shaking the spiders from his shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One is stuck in his sleeve, and he has to dance to get it out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even then, he still keeps twitching, convinced another one is left behind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At his feet, the gravel road has returned, smooth and dusty and comforting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ahead lies a tiny one-street town -- smaller even than Ashton -- with powerlines emerging from the woods to feed it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dangling from the line above he sees two dozen pairs of shoes, their laces tied together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passes a sign that reads "Welcome To Spectre!"
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE TOWN OF SPECTRE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a main street with stores on each side: Cole's Pharmacy, Talbot's Five and Dime, Al's Country Store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everything is old, but this isn't a ghost town.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In fact, there's a group of about 20 CITIZENS spilling out to see Edward approach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Most are smiling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are even a few tears of joy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What's more, all of these people are barefoot.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAN'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Friend!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A forty-year old man named BEAMEN comes out of the seed store to greet Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Friendly but a little drunk, he's the closest thing the town has to a mayor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's carrying a clipboard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Welcome to ya.
{DIALOGUE}: What's your name?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beamen checks the clipboard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not finding the name, he flips forward a few pages.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still looking...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Bloom like a flower?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{DIALOGUE}: Here!
{DIALOGUE}: Right here.
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom.
{DIALOGUE}: We weren't expecting you yet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still confused...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You were expecting me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Not yet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A helpful woman named MILDRED chimes in:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILDRED
{DIALOGUE}: You must have taken a shortcut.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I did.
{DIALOGUE}: It nearly killed me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Mmm-hmm.
{DIALOGUE}: Life'll do that to you.
{DIALOGUE}: And truthfully, the long way is easier, but it's longer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILDRED
{DIALOGUE}: Much longer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: And you're here now, and that's what matters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beamen's daughter JENNY (8) hides behind her father, peering around to look at the handsome stranger.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What is this place?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: The town of Spectre.
{DIALOGUE}: Best kept secret in Alabama.
{DIALOGUE}: Says here you're from Ashton, right?
{DIALOGUE}: Last person we had from Ashton was Norther Winslow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: The poet?
{DIALOGUE}: What ever happened to him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: He's still here.
{DIALOGUE}: Let me buy you a drink.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll tell you all about it.
{DIALOGUE}: Hell, I'll have him tell you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I've gotta meet somebody.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm already running late.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He didn't mean it as a joke, but for some reason, everyone's laughing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Son, I already told you.
{DIALOGUE}: You're early.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BEAMEN'S HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting at the kitchen table, Edward takes a second slice of apple pie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He and Beamen are joined by NORTHER WINSLOW (30), who fancies himself a cultured artist, though he's never left the state.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Now tell me if that isn't the best pie you ever ate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It truly is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: UNDER THE TABLE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Jenny is stealthily untying the laces on Edward's shoes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Everything here tastes better.
{DIALOGUE}: Even the water is sweet.
{DIALOGUE}: Never gets too hot, too cold, too humid.
{DIALOGUE}: At night the wind goes through the trees and you'd swear there was a whole symphony out there, playing just for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, Jenny YANKS OFF Edward's shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She races for the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Hey!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He chases after her.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TOWN / MAIN STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she runs, Jenny ties Edward's laces together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the edge of town, she tosses the shoes up and around the power line -- a perfect throw.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's no way he's ever getting them down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The gathered citizens of Spectre CHEER for Edward, who is confused and overwhelmed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The women hug him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Men shake his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still focused on his shoes...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Wait!
{DIALOGUE}: I need those!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: There is no softer ground than town.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILDRED
{DIALOGUE}: That rhymes!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: He is our poet laureate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The townsfolk continue to congratulate Edward...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes in a dream, you'll visit places that seem instantly familiar, filled with friends you've never met.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. UNDER A TREE - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward sits with Norther Winslow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The fireflies are out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Thousands of them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A man might travel his entire life and never find a place so inviting.
{DIALOGUE}: My journey had scarcely begun, and I had arrived.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Norther hands him his noteboook.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: I've been working on this poem for 12 years.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Really.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: There's a lot of expectation.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to disappoint my fans.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It's only three lines long.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Norther grabs his notebook back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: This is why you don't show work in progress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Norther, do you ever regret not making it to Paris?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: I can't imagine any place better than here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You're a poet.
{DIALOGUE}: You oughta be able to.
{DIALOGUE}: And maybe if you'd seen more, you could.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Norther doesn't answer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just goes back to his notebook.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BY THE RIVER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By the light of the full moon, Edward soaks his feet in the water, trying to make sense of it all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Key to the City dangles around his neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stares at himself in the reflection.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's then that a WOMAN emerges at the far side of the river.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No telling where she came from -- she must have been swimming underwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We never see her face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stands in the river with her bare back to Edward, squeezing the water out of her golden hair, oblivious to his presence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is breathless.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the first woman he's seen in her natural state, and he doesn't dare move lest he frighten her away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then he sees the snake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a cottonmouth, has to be.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It leaves a break in the water, its small reptilian head aiming for her flesh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's no decision to be made.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On pure instinct, Edward dives in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swims as hard as can,
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GRABBING THE SNAKE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: just as it's about to strike.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The woman dives back underwater, understandably terrified that a man is coming at her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No, it's okay!
{DIALOGUE}: I got it.
{DIALOGUE}: I got the snake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the splashing subsides, Edward looks at what he holds in his hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Which isn't a snake at all, but rather a common stick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And a non-threatening one at that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While Edward ponders his mistake, he looks around to discover that the Girl in the River is gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He never even saw her face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Wait!
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward keeps expecting her to surface, somewhere, but she never does.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands alone in the river, wondering what tricks his eyes are playing on him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BY THE RIVER - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A GIRL'S VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: There's leeches in there!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks to the bank, where young Jenny Hill is watching him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Did you see that woman?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: What did she look like?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Well, she... uh...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Was she nekkid?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Embarrassed to admit it...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{META_DATA}: (matter-of-fact)
{DIALOGUE}: It's not a woman, it's a fish.
{DIALOGUE}: No one ever catches her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Given the day he's had so far, Edward isn't inclined to follow up on the issue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts to wade back to the bank.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Fish looks diff'rent to diff'rent people.
{DIALOGUE}: My daddy said it looked like the coon dog he had when he was kid, back from the dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward climbs up onto the shore, completely drenched.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls up his pant legs to reveal three shiny leeches clinging to his skin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Shoot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts to work pulling them off.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PATH BACK TO TOWN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward and Jenny walk back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: How old are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Eighteen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm eight.
{DIALOGUE}: That means when I'm eighteen, you'll be 28.
{DIALOGUE}: And when I'm 28, you'll only be 38.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (a little wary)
{DIALOGUE}: You're pretty good at arithmetic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: And when I'm 38, you'll be 48.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's not much difference at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eager to get off this subject...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Sure is a lot now, though, huh?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Edward and Jenny approach Main Street, they find "downtown" has been transformed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lanterns and streamers hang on cables across the street, and a small stage has been built at one end to hold FIDDLERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The whole town is there in celebration of its newest citizen, Edward Bloom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before he can protest, two WOMEN have grabbed him by the arms, pulling him in to dance with them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The resulting dance number seems both choreographed and complete chaos.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From FARMER to BAKER'S WIFE, everyone wants to dance with Edward, who finds himself tossed around like a stick caught in a whirlpool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, he's having a blast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny grabs both his hands, and they spin wildly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beamen plucks his LAUGHING daughter away to dance with her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then Mildred cuts in to dance with Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's hard to hear over the MUSIC.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILDRED
{DIALOGUE}: Jenny thinks you're quite a catch.
{DIALOGUE}: We all do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (not hearing)
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILDRED
{DIALOGUE}: I said you're quite a catch!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward stops dancing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then he heads for the edge of the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beamen is there, with Jenny on his shoulders.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I have to leave.
{DIALOGUE}: Tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: This town is everything a man could ask for.
{DIALOGUE}: And if I were to end up here, I'd consider myself lucky.
{DIALOGUE}: But the fact is, I'm not ready to end up anywhere.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{DIALOGUE}: No one's ever left.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: How are you gonna make it without your shoes?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I suspect it will hurt a lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that, Edward walks down Main Street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The townspeople stop dancing, disbelieving, some shaking their heads.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Poor Edward Bloom's gone crazy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEAMEN
{META_DATA}: (calling after him)
{DIALOGUE}: You won't find a better place!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't expect to.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny runs to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She'd tackle him if she could.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Promise me you'll come back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I promise.
{DIALOGUE}: Someday.
{DIALOGUE}: When I'm really supposed to.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not good enough, but it will have to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward keeps walking.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE DARK FOREST - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS SHOTS: Edward negotiates the thorns in his bare feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's horrible.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost unendurable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then it gets worse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The trees ahead are moving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At first, it just seems to be the wind blowing the branches, but as we hear the wood CRACKING and GROANING, there's no mistaking it: they're trying to block him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Snake-like WHITE ROOTS shoot out of the ground, grabbing for his ankles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leaps up, kicking off one tree trunk to grab another one's branches.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swings off, lands and rolls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now all the trees are moving to block him, their dark shapes towering over him in the flashes of LIGHTNING.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As difficult as it was to reach Spectre, I was fated to get there eventually.
{DIALOGUE}: After all, no man can avoid reaching the end of his life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he ducks under branches, the chain holding the Key to the City gets caught.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's almost strangled, but the chain finally breaks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The silver key disappears into the mud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scrambling forward, he looks for a way out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the trees have encircled him, their spiky crowns bending down to crush him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He SCREAMS up at the night, until his breath is gone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: And then I realized, this wasn't the end of my life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a sudden calm...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (aloud)
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't how I die.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another lightning FLASH, and suddenly the trees are back where they've always been.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is lying shoeless and torn in a muddy puddle, staring up at the rain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And LAUGHING.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His bare foot steps onto asphalt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A DEEP VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Friend!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward turns to see
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: KARL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: to his right, coming down the larger, paved road.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: What happened to your shoes?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks down at his muddy, bloody feet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: They got ahead of me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With that, the men start walking down the larger road.
{META_DATA}: CROSSFADE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DINING ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward and Will sit at opposite ends of the table, with Sandra and Josephine in the middle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Although Edward has a small plate of food in front of him, he hasn't touched it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's exhausted from the trip downstairs, but determined to maintain the family dinner ritual.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other three eat awkwardly, each CLINK and SCRAPE of a knife or fork resonating.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will finally breaks the silence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know if you've seen it, but Josephine has some photos in the most recent Newsweek.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Really!
{DIALOGUE}: That's wonderful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I spent a week in Morocco for the story.
{DIALOGUE}: It was incredible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: We'll have to pick up a copy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Will scoops out another serving of potatoes, Edward suddenly speaks:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know if you're aware of this, Josephine, but African parrots, in their native home of the Congo -- they speak only French.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All three stop to listen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (amused)
{DIALOGUE}: Really.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You're lucky to get four words out of them in English.
{DIALOGUE}: But if you were to walk through the jungle, you'd hear them speaking the most elaborate French.
{DIALOGUE}: Those parrots talk about everything: politics, movies, fashion -- everything but religion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Taking the bait...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Why not religion, Dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It's rude to talk about religion.
{DIALOGUE}: You never know who you're going to offend.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Josephine actually went to the Congo last year.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, so you know.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GROCERY STORE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will shakes a shopping cart free from the pile-up while his mother checks her list.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: AT THE PRODUCE SECTION
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra starts to bag string beans.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Mom, would you say you understand Dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Of course.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What I mean is, do you really know what's going on in his head?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How is that possible?
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, you try to ask him a question and suddenly it's another one of his stories.
{META_DATA}: (decidedly)
{DIALOGUE}: You can't honestly say you know him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Will, I do.
{DIALOGUE}: And don't presume things you don't know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's more amused than annoyed, but Will is entering dangerous territory.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Would you say you understand Josephine?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: But that's a different...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: No it's not.
{DIALOGUE}: It's exactly the same.
{DIALOGUE}: Your father and I met, we dated, and we married -- we chose each other -- because we understood each other on some fundamental level.
{DIALOGUE}: Just the same as you two.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She moves on to the carrots.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Josephine and I have a lot in common.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, you both think William Bloom is a very smart man.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: The problem is, you only see me as your mother, and not as someone's wife.
{DIALOGUE}: And I've been his wife longer than I've been your mother.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't discount that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: True.
{DIALOGUE}: But I've known him my whole life, and I don't feel like I know him at all.
{DIALOGUE}: Or ever will.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a look, Sandra acknowledges the stakes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I know it's not easy.
{DIALOGUE}: Just remember, he didn't choose to be your father and you didn't choose to be his son.
{DIALOGUE}: You just ended up together.
{DIALOGUE}: You could pick numbers out of a dark bag and it'd be just the same.
{DIALOGUE}: If you ask me, it's a wonder parents and children can stand each other at all.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: But I understand you, Mom.
{DIALOGUE}: I always have.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Well, clearly you don't.
{DIALOGUE}: But I'm not the mystery you're trying to solve right now.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AT THE CHECKOUT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the CASHIER, Sandra hands over her coupons.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will is approaching with a Newsweek magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two checkstands over, an ATTRACTIVE BLONDE WOMAN in her 50's
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is getting her change.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though she's Sandra's generation, she carries herself like a much younger woman, with blue jeans and sneakers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She accidentally makes eye contact with Will as he passes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HOLD ON the woman, who tracks Will as he reaches Sandra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's hard to read her reaction: does she recognize him, or just find him attractive?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will notices the gaze.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The woman turns away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will racks his brain -- does he know this woman?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Before I forget, your father has papers in the basement I'd like you to go through.
{DIALOGUE}: I wouldn't know what's important.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (distracted)
{DIALOGUE}: Mom, do you know who that is?
{DIALOGUE}: Blonde hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra looks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a beat, the Blonde Woman turns again, semi-casually.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Noticing that both Will and Sandra are looking, she smiles a little before taking her cart to leave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (no idea)
{DIALOGUE}: Was she one of your teachers?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: But it's weird.
{DIALOGUE}: She seemed to recognize me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (to the cashier)
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know who that is?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Cashier turns to look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can only get a profile as the woman leaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CASHIER
{DIALOGUE}: Never seen her before.
{DIALOGUE}: Pretty, though.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST BEDROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A portable fan quietly WHIRRS in the corner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Turned low, the RADIO on the nightstand is playing a call-in AM sports show, just a wash of background chatter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward lies asleep on his back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the window, Josephine quietly lowers the shade.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She reaches over Edward to switch off the radio.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stirs from the silence -- he wasn't fully asleep -- and sees Josephine stretched over him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (playfully lecherous)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smiles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: How are you feeling?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I was dreaming.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: What were you dreaming about?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to recollect, but it's already gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine motions, is it okay for her to sit on the bed?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't usually remember unless they're especially portentous.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what that word means, portentous?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She shakes her head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Means when you dream about something that's going to happen.
{META_DATA}: (beat, gathering)
{DIALOGUE}: Like one night, I had a dream where this crow came and told me, "Your Aunt is going to die."
{DIALOGUE}: I was so scared I woke up my parents.
{DIALOGUE}: They told me it was just a dream, to go back to bed.
{DIALOGUE}: But the next morning, my Aunt Stacy was dead.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: That's terrible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Terrible for her, but think about me, young boy with that kind of power.
{DIALOGUE}: Wasn't three weeks later that the crow came back to me in a dream and said, "Your Grampa is going to die."
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I ran right back to my parents.
{DIALOGUE}: My father said, no, Gramps is fine, but I could see there was trepidation.
{DIALOGUE}: And true enough, that next morning my Grampa was dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits up a bit in bed, his strength returning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: For the next couple weeks, I didn't have another dream.
{DIALOGUE}: Until one night the crow came back and said, "Your Daddy is going to die."
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I didn't know what to do.
{DIALOGUE}: But finally I told my father.
{DIALOGUE}: And he said not to worry, but I could tell he was rattled.
{DIALOGUE}: That next day, he wasn't himself, always looking around, waiting for something to drop on his head.
{DIALOGUE}: Because the crow didn't tell how it was going to happen, just those words: your Daddy is going to die.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, he went into town early and was gone for a long time.
{DIALOGUE}: And when he finally came back, he looked terrible, like he was waiting for the axe to fall all day.
{DIALOGUE}: He said to my mother, "Good God.
{DIALOGUE}: I just had the worst day of my life."
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: "You think you've had a bad day," she said.
{DIALOGUE}: "This morning the milkman dropped dead on the porch!"
{DIALOGUE}: Josephine smiles, a half-laugh, which gets him smiling too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, deadpan...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Because see, my mother was banging the milkman.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: No, I understand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: He was slipping her a little extra cream.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She nods, a bit more of a laugh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: He was filling her basket.
{DIALOGUE}: He was making deliveries around back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Edward continues, she can't help but laugh harder, especially as the metaphors get more vulgar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: He was buttering her rolls.
{DIALOGUE}: Pumping her churn.
{DIALOGUE}: Splashing milk in her box.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Stop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: They were squeezing the cheese.
{DIALOGUE}: Clanking the bottles.
{DIALOGUE}: Licking the popsicle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's starting to cry from laughing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Cracking the eggs and making an omelet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With that, he stops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She regains her composure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Spooning the sherbet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Can I take your picture?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You don't need a picture.
{DIALOGUE}: Just look up handsome in the dictionary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Please?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rolls his eyes, why not.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine leaves, heading down the hall to get her camera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We STAY WITH Edward in bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: I have photos from the wedding to show you.
{DIALOGUE}: There's a great one of you and my father.
{DIALOGUE}: I had an extra print made.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward grimaces, a flash of pain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Around others, he's hiding how much it hurts, but alone we can see how bad it is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He controls his breathing, trying to push through it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I want to see pictures of your wedding.
{DIALOGUE}: I've never seen any.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She returns with her camera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward smiles, doing a good job masking the pain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That's because we didn't have a wedding.
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother-in-law was never supposed to marry me.
{DIALOGUE}: She was engaged to somebody else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (loading film)
{DIALOGUE}: I never knew.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Will never told you that?
{META_DATA}: (she shakes her head)
{DIALOGUE}: Probably just as well.
{DIALOGUE}: He would have told it all wrong anyway.
{DIALOGUE}: All the facts and none of the flavor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, so this is a tall tale?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it's not a short one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A devilish smile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pushing past Edward, we settle on the whirling fan.
{META_DATA}: MATCH CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SPINNING PINWHEEL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: held by a LITTLE BOY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's slumped over his FATHER's shoulder, being carried towards a big-top tent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OLYMPIA CIRCUS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...where the second-rate carnival is parked for the moment in an Alabama field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To the left, we spot Edward, 20-ish, halfway through a bag of peanuts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's still carrying the backpack we saw earlier, and scratched up from his trip through Spectre.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I had just left Ashton, and was on my way to discover my destiny.
{DIALOGUE}: Not knowing what that would be exactly, I explored every opportunity that presented itself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Joining the crowd, he heads into the big-top.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG TOP - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A troupe of STILT-WALKING FIREBREATHERS finishes their act to tremendous APPLAUSE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the performers clear away, the circus' owner-and-ringmaster AMOS CALLOWAY (50) approaches the stands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He may only be four feet tall, but Amos has a titanic presence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Ladies and Gentlemen, you may think you've seen the unusual.
{DIALOGUE}: You may think you've seen the bizarre.
{DIALOGUE}: But I've travelled to the five corners of the world, and let me tell you, I've never seen anything like this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From behind Amos, CARNIES start rolling a massive ball towards the crowd.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: When I found this man, he was picking oranges in Florida.
{DIALOGUE}: His fellow workers called him El Penumbra -- The Shadow -- because when you were working beside him, he blocked out the daylight.
{DIALOGUE}: He could take a whole tree in his hands and shake off the fruit.
{DIALOGUE}: I had to pay his crew boss $10,000 just so I could take him with me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos comes up to a MIDDLE-AGED WOMAN in the first row, a quieter moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Not to alarm you, Ma'am.
{DIALOGUE}: But if this man wanted to, he could crush your head between his toes.
{META_DATA}: (she trembles)
{DIALOGUE}: But he won't.
{META_DATA}: (a long beat)
{DIALOGUE}: He's not going to hurt her, folks, because he's our own Gentle Giant.
{DIALOGUE}: Ladies and Gentlemen, I give you Colossus!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The carnies back away from the ball as a deep DRUM ROLL begins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A moment, then the ball starts to bulge from inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A foot suddenly bursts out from within.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GASPS from the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That foot is massive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the stands, Edward looks closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Intrigued.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the drum beat intensifies, a second foot breaks out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Followed by hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally, the head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is COLOSSUS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From a very LOW ANGLE, we look up to see just how massive he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He seems to fill the Heavens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With his shaved head and giant club, he seems more ogre than man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the bandstands, a YOUNG BOY's jaw drops in awe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Colossus walks down the row, letting the crowd get a better look at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some reach out to touch him, disbelieving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tight spotlight follows him, revealing faces in the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Colossus passes Edward, who seems unimpressed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans with the spotlight, WHISTLING to get the big man's attention.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He points to the edge of the stands, where his friend is sitting on the dirt --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: KARL THE GIANT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: stands up, so big the spotlight has to widen just to hold him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's a good foot taller than Colossus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a GASP from the crowd, along with nervous anticipation -- what will happen next?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Amos, stunned, megaphone dangling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Colossus, realizing the gig is up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a resigned shrug, he rests his club on his shoulder and walks away into the shadows.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG-TOP - NIGHT / LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the stands empty, Edward and Karl talk to Amos.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: What's his name?
{DIALOGUE}: Does he talk?
{DIALOGUE}: It's not important.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KARL
{DIALOGUE}: Karl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me Karl, have you ever heard of the term "involuntary servitude?"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl shakes his head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: "Unconscionable contract?"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Great, great.
{DIALOGUE}: That's fantastic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It was on that night Karl met his destiny.
{DIALOGUE}: And I met mine.
{DIALOGUE}: Almost.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG TOP - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Amos pulls Karl aside to give him the hard sell, Edward notices a BEAUTIFUL YOUNG WOMAN (16) leaving with her family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's wearing a blue dress and hat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For no good reason, she looks back at Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two make eye contact.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And as they do, all motion FREEZES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fiery baton remains mid-twirl, flames locked in place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A spilled box of popcorn hangs in mid-air, each kernel like a snowflake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even the elephant is mid-poop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only Edward is free to move, winding his way between the frozen bodies, ducking underneath arms to get closer and closer to this woman.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: They say when you meet the love of your life, time stops.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's true.
{DIALOGUE}: What they don't tell you, is that once time starts again, it moves extra fast to catch up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, everything RUSHES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd becomes a blur, and the young woman is lost in its wake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now it's Edward who's frozen, helpless in time.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. DIRT PARKING LOT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward checks in windows as cars pull out, searching for his fated love.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not finding her, he becomes more frantic, running down the rows.
{META_DATA}: CROSSFADE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE EMPTY LOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Colossus is thumbing for a ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The last pickup truck stops and lets him climb in back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the truck pulls out, it passes a dejected Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He'll never find that girl, the love of his life.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG-TOP - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos leans over so Karl can sign a contract on his back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He spots Edward walking back into the tent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Hey kid!
{DIALOGUE}: Your friend just made himself a star.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That's great.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos hands off the contract to a CLOWN.
{META_DATA}: (INTRODUCING)
{DIALOGUE}: My attorney, Mr. Soggybottom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Good to meet you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Soggybottom HONKS his horn, then waddles off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with you, kid?
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't seen a customer so depressed since the elephant sat on that farmer's wife.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Get it?
{DIALOGUE}: "Depressed?"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl chuckles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: See!
{DIALOGUE}: The big guy likes it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I just saw the woman I'm going to marry, I know it.
{DIALOGUE}: But then I lost her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Tough break.
{DIALOGUE}: Most men have to get married before they lose their wives.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (with absolute conviction)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to spend the rest of my life looking for her.
{DIALOGUE}: That or die alone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus, kid.
{META_DATA}: (realizing)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me guess.
{DIALOGUE}: Real pretty, blonde hair, blue hat?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Yes!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: I know her uncle.
{DIALOGUE}: Friends of the family.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Who is she?
{DIALOGUE}: Where does she live?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Kid.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't waste your time.
{DIALOGUE}: She's out of your league.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Amos starts to walk away, Edward hurries to catch up with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl follows as well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What do you mean?
{DIALOGUE}: You don't even know me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Sure I do.
{DIALOGUE}: You were hot shit back in Hickville, but here in the real world, you got squat.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have a plan.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have a job.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have anything but the clothes on your back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I've got a whole backpack full of clothes!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He points to the bleachers, where no backpack is to be found.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (realizing)
{DIALOGUE}: Someone stole my backpack.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Kid, you were a big fish in a small pond.
{DIALOGUE}: This here is the ocean, and you're drowning.
{DIALOGUE}: Take my advice and go back to Puddleville.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll be happy there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Getting in front of Amos, Edward stops him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Wait.
{DIALOGUE}: You said I don't have a plan.
{DIALOGUE}: I do.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to find that girl and marry her and spend the rest of my life with her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos smiles, amused.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't have a job, but I would have a job if you gave me one.
{DIALOGUE}: And I may not have much, but I have more determination than any man you're ever going to meet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry, kid.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't do charity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'll work night and day, and you won't have to pay me.
{DIALOGUE}: You just have to tell me who she is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos takes a long look at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ultimately, there's no way he can say no.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shrugs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What the hell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Every month you work for me, I'll tell you one thing about her.
{DIALOGUE}: That's my final offer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward shakes Amos's hand before he can retract the offer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We move into a MONTAGE:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG TOP CENTER RING - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON Edward, smiling nervously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His head is tilted to the side, and as we PULL BACK, we see why: he's holding it in a MASSIVE LION's open mouth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The beast's sharp teeth are just poking his skin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: If the lion so much as flinches, Edward is dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The CROWD applauds, which makes the lion antsy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Which makes Edward antsier.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: From that moment on, I did everything Mr. Calloway asked, and a lot of things he didn't.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd go three days without stopping to eat, and four days without sleeping.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE HYDRA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes droopy from lack of sleep, Edward mans the whirling amusement park ride.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The only thing that kept me going was the promise of meeting the girl who would be my wife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nodding off, Edward falls backward, into the path of the spinning arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of the Hydra cars hits him square in the gut, throwing him up and away, sailing 200 feet through the air.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward chases a costumed pig, tripping over tent cords, falling in the mud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His hunt leads him through the back of a tent, where he's unwittingly stepped in front of a line of motorized birds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To the left, CUSTOMERS are shooting with rifles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He dodges four SHOTS that knock down the birds around him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He catches his breath, lucky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then a half-blind OLD WOMAN pulls her trigger, hitting him in the shoulder.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BEHIND A TENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl the Giant bandages Edward's arm as well as he can.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos is walking past.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Calloway!
{DIALOGUE}: It's been a month today.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos stops, looks at the young man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: This girl, the love of your life.
{DIALOGUE}: Her favorite flower is daffodils.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PUSH IN on Edward, enraptured by the concept.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Daffodils.
{META_DATA}: (to Karl)
{DIALOGUE}: Daffodils!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STABLES - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward shovels shit in the nastiest stables you've ever seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But all he can think about is...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: Daffodils!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The wonder of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes back to shoveling, a smile on his face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: True to his word, every month Amos would tell me something new about the woman of my dreams.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. A DARK PLACE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON Edward, lost in quiet reverie, pondering his latest bit of information.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: College!
{DIALOGUE}: She's going to college!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A sudden EXPLOSION as Edward is shot...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BIG TOP - NIGHT [CONTINUOUS]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...out of a giant cannon.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STABLES - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under a full moon, Edward feeds the animals.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: Music!
{DIALOGUE}: She likes music.
{DIALOGUE}: I like music too!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Over the months, I learned a lot about the woman I was going to marry, but not her name, and not where to find her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That time had come.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I couldn't wait any longer.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AMOS CALLOWAY'S TRAILER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under a full moon, Edward walks up to the battered camper, and is about to knock when he notices it's rocking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not just that, there's MOANING coming from inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Edward KNOCKS anyway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Calloway!
{DIALOGUE}: It's Edward Bloom.
{DIALOGUE}: I need to talk to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, the rocking and moaning stop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then the door handle begins to RATTLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It seems to be stuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward turns the knob.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, the door BURSTS OPEN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is knocked down by a massive black dog, biggest you've ever seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It has green glowing eyes and a lick of fire for a tongue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward wrestles with the beast, its mouth snapping at his throat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Blocking with an arm, Edward tries to push himself free, but the creature's hands -- it has hands instead of paws -- hold on tight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Entwined, they roll across the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other nearby CARNIES scatter for cover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Soggybottom pulls a revolver out of his clown suit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Loads a silver bullet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward finally succeeds in throwing the beast off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rolls to his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hell hound squares back on its haunches, GROWLING, ready for another leap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Soggybottom sheds a clown tear, aiming the revolver at the dog.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the last moment...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No, wait!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward moves just as Mr. Soggybottom FIRES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bullet catches Edward in the shoulder, knocking him down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The carnies GASP.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Licking its chops, the dog approaches the helpless Edward, who feels the ground around him, looking for some kind of weapon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finds only a small stick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He waves it at the dog, ready to strike it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Like magic, the dog's whole demeanor changes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It bounces excitedly, ready to play fetch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seeing an opportunity, Edward throws the stick as far as he can.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The dog bounds after it,
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SMASHING DOWN THREE CARS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It returns a beat later with the flaming stick, which it drops at Edward's feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Its tail whips back and forth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It was that night I discovered that most things you consider evil or wicked are simply lonely, and lacking in the social niceties.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward throws the stick again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The dog takes off in a new direction.
{META_DATA}: TRANSITION TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD - PRE-DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exhausted from playing fetch all night, Edward throws the stick into the woods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The still-spry dog goes after it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's gone for a long time, long enough that Edward becomes concerned.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He follows it into the woods.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WOODS - DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos Calloway stands up behind a bush, buck naked and hairy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He still has the stick in his mouth, which he takes out as Edward approaches.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Didn't kill anything, did I?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: A few rabbits, but I think one of them was already dead.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: That would explain the indigestion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward tosses him his jacket to cover his privates.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: I was wrong about you kid.
{DIALOGUE}: You may not have much, but what you got, you got a lot of.
{DIALOGUE}: You could get any girl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: There's only one I want.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Her name is Sandra Templeton.
{DIALOGUE}: She's going to Auburn.
{DIALOGUE}: The semester's almost over, so you better hurry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: AMOS
{DIALOGUE}: Good luck, kid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward walks away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then starts running.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has to get there as soon as possible.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos sits down and scratches his ear with his foot.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BIG TOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward shakes Karl's giant hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They hug.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: After saying my goodbyes, I hopped three trains to get to Auburn that afternoon.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. AUBURN UNIVERSITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We DESCEND ON the main quad, to find Edward Bloom dunking his head in the fountain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He changes out of his grubby shirt into a new one, just out of the package.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the mid-1960's, but by the conservative dress of the passing STUDENTS, it could be any era.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SORORITY HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward stands with a bouquet of daffodils in front of a half- open door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the crack we can see the edge of a YOUNG WOMAN, talking in hushed tones with another girl we can't see.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally, a decision is reached.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens to reveal the woman of Edward's dreams, Sandra Kay Templeton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's effortlessly beautiful, pure and simple as sunlight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can't believe he's finally reached her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He half-laughs, nervous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That makes her laugh, not sure what's going on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You don't know me, but my name is Edward Bloom and I am in love with you.
{DIALOGUE}: I've spent the last three years working to find out who you are.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been shot and stabbed and trampled a few times, had my ribs broken twice, but it's all worth it to see you here, now, and to finally get to talk to you.
{DIALOGUE}: Because I am destined to marry you.
{DIALOGUE}: I knew that from the first moment I saw you at the circus.
{DIALOGUE}: And I know it now more than ever.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON SANDRA, overwhelmed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All she can finally think of to say is...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Don't need to apologize to me.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, I'm the luckiest person you're going to find today...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She puts her hand on the door frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On her left ring finger, we see a diamond.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: No I'm sorry, I..
{DIALOGUE}: I'm engaged to be married.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON EDWARD as his heart falls 20 floors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to suppress the reaction, put on a brave front.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: But you're wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: I do know you, at least by reputation.
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom from Ashton.
{DIALOGUE}: See, I'm actually engaged to a boy from Ashton.
{DIALOGUE}: Don Price.
{DIALOGUE}: He was a few years older than you.
{META_DATA}: FLASHCUTS TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CREEPY OLD HOUSE - THE GATE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Don Price shines his flashlight on Edward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS H.S. ATHLETIC COMPETITIONS 93
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Recapping earlier football, baseball and basketball highlights, we find Edward beats Don every time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE STREET CORNER / ASHTON PARADE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A smoking Don Price crushes his cigarette as Edward leaves town.
{META_DATA}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT/INT. SORORITY HOUSE - THE DOORWAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is dumbstruck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With all the strength he can muster...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Well.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry to have bothered you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and walks down the front steps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stays in the doorway for a few beats, feeling genuinely horrible for what's happened.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But eventually she goes back inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear GIGGLES from inside as her sorority sisters get to the bottom of this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Stop it.
{DIALOGUE}: It's not funny.
{DIALOGUE}: That poor boy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LEAD Edward as he walks away, tears just starting to form.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Fate has a cruel way of circling around on you.
{DIALOGUE}: After all this work to leave Ashton, the girl I loved was now engaged to one of its biggest jerks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He EXITS FRAME, leaving only the sorority house in the background.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: There's a time when a man needs to fight, and a time when he needs to accept that his destiny is lost, that the ship has sailed, and that only a fool would continue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward steps back INTO FRAME, looking at the sorority house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The truth is, I've always been a fool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We CIRCLE as he shouts:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Sandra Templeton!
{DIALOGUE}: I love you!
{DIALOGUE}: And I am going to marry you!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SORORITY HOUSE FOYER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra and her SISTERS peer out through the curtains.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Is this guy crazy?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. LECTURE HALL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tweedy ECONOMICS PROFESSOR continues his explanation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra isn't paying a lot of attention.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He switches on the overhead projector without looking at it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a TITTER from the STUDENTS, but he doesn't notice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A classmate nudges Sandra, who looks up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Written on the projector is "I Love Sandra Templeton."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's horrified and excited at the same time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The professor finally notices what's written there.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. QUAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walking with her books, Sandra shakes her head, disbelieving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We look up to the blue sky, where a giant sky-written heart floats in the wind.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SANDRA'S BEDROOM - [THE NEXT] MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At her Sisters' prompting, a just-woken Sandra looks out the second-story window to find the lawn filled with
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TEN THOUSAND DAFFODILS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward stands amid the sea of flowers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's waited there six hours.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SORORITY HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra walks out to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's smiling, confused, joyful and scared.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All down Greek Street, STUDENTS are coming out to see the display.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Daffodils?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: They're your favorite flower.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: How did you get so many?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I called everywhere in five states and explained this was the only way I could get my wife to marry me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Out of nowhere, a tear drops down Sandra's cheek.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She wipes it off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: You don't even know me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I have the rest of my life to find out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From down the street...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A MAN'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Sandra!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: It's Don.
{DIALOGUE}: Promise me you won't hurt him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: If that's what you want, I swear to it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The adult DON PRICE arrives.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's 230 pounds of football- playing, Skynyrd-loving, fraternity-proud muscle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And he's pissed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A gang of his BROTHERS walk behind him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: Bloom!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Don.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: What the hell are you doing?
{DIALOGUE}: This is my girl.
{DIALOGUE}: Mine!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't know she belonged to anybody.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don Price decks him, knocking him down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward gets right back up, but makes no move to defend himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Unfazed, Don slugs him again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Stop it!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{META_DATA}: (ignoring)
{DIALOGUE}: What the matter, Bloom?
{DIALOGUE}: Too scared to fight back?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I promised I wouldn't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don shrugs, fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then proceeds to kick Edward's ass nine ways to Sunday.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: While I took the beating of a lifetime, it was Don Price who was ultimately defeated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the ass-whupping continues, we
{META_DATA}: INTERCUT WITH:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FRATERNITY HOUSE BATHROOM - DAY [FLASHFORWARD]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting on the can, Don Price pinches a loaf while reading the new Playboy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: All the physical activity had worsened a congenital valve defect.
{DIALOGUE}: Put simply, his heart wasn't strong enough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don Price squeezes down hard, trying to shit the unshittable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, he grasps his chest and collapses face-first on the tile.
{META_DATA}: MATCH CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WITCH'S HOUSE / GATE - NIGHT [FLASHBACK]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same image of Don's dead face on the tile is reflected in The Eye.
{META_DATA}: RETURNING BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. THE SORORITY HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The thrashing continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward somehow fights his way back to his feet, ready to be knocked down again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Don!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don is about to slug Edward again when he turns.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra pulls off her engagement ring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's an audible AHH!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: from her sisters, and an OHH!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: from Don's brothers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I will never marry you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Don stands stunned, his mind reeling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward, whose eyes are swollen almost shut, keeps waiting for the next punch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Where is it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What's going on?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DON PRICE
{DIALOGUE}: What.
{DIALOGUE}: You love this guy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: He's almost a stranger and I prefer him to you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands him the ring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another beat, then Don storms off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But not before decking Edward one last time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra leans over Edward's broken body.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His head lies on the daffodils.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: How can I convince you to stop?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Go out with me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles, his teeth bloody.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the crowd of students APPLAUDS and CHEERS, we CRANE UP above the flowered battlefield.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As it turned out, Sandra was able to keep her same date at the chapel.
{DIALOGUE}: Only the groom had changed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the MUSIC reaches a crescendo, we suddenly...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST ROOM - NIGHT [PRESENT]
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you said you didn't have a church wedding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we were all set to, but there was a complication.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches for his glass of water, but Josephine already has it for him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She watches him while he slowly drinks the entire glass, thirstier than he imagined.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While he's drinking, we...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPSTAIRS HALLWAY - NIGHT [CONTINUOUS]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will, back from the grocery store, reaches the top of the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hears voices coming from the bedroom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Is it the medicine that's making you thirsty?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Truth is, I've been thirsty my whole life.
{DIALOGUE}: Never really known why.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will quietly approaches the door, not exactly sneaking, but not exactly announcing his presence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door is open a few inches, letting him look in on his father and his wife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INTERCUT HALLWAY / BEDROOM
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: There was one time when I was eleven...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (gently)
{DIALOGUE}: You were talking about your wedding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't forget.
{DIALOGUE}: I was just working on a tangent.
{DIALOGUE}: See, most men, they'll tell a story straight through, and it won't be complicated, but it won't be interesting either.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I like your stories.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: And I like you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He doesn't let the moment linger with undue sentimentality.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a story to be told.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Now.
{DIALOGUE}: The thing about working for a circus is you don't have a regular address, and after three years I had a lot of undelivered mail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the hallway, Will shifts to a new position, letting himself listen to the story one more time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: During the four weeks I was in the hospital, the postmaster finally caught up with me.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bruised and bandaged, Edward sorts through a big bag of mail with help from Sandra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rips open an official-looking letter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reading it, his face drops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FLUTE and DRUM, music rising to a military cadence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It turned out that while my heart belonged to Sandra, the rest of my body belonged to the U.S. Government.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ARMY AIRPLANE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a buzz cut and paratrooper gear, Edward squats with a dozen other SOLDIERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The noise of the ENGINES is deafening, but Edward is engrossed in an Asian phrasebook.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A hitch in the Army was up to three years at that point, and having waited three years just to meet Sandra, I knew I couldn't survive being away from her that long.
{DIALOGUE}: So I took every hazardous assignment I could find, with the hope of getting my time down to less than a year.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The JUMP LEADER yells...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUMP LEADER
{DIALOGUE}: GO!
{DIALOGUE}: GO!
{DIALOGUE}: GO!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One by one the men jump out, their chutes clipped to a main line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When his time comes, Edward leaps...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...but he's stuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His cord is caught up in the assembly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He twists and struggles, trying to free himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking down, he can see the white parachutes disappearing into the darkness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're already long gone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Digging a knife out of his pocket, Edward gets to work cutting through the cable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It finally POPS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward jumps from the plane.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. OUTSIDE STAGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A THOUSAND CHINESE SOLDIERS sit, bored, watching the equivalent of a U.S.O. show.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CHINESE VENTRILOQUIST is on stage with his Communist puppet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We have no idea what they're saying to each other, but every act is fundamentally the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The EMCEE comes on to usher him off the stage before he's finished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Ventriloquist protests, but finally gives in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Emcee makes a "shoot him in the neck" motion to one of the ARMED GUARDS off-stage.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HIGH ABOVE THE STAGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LOOK DOWN with Edward, who is drifting right for the stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can't steer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's helpless.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But then, a BLAST of fireworks from the sides of the stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lights go out as a DRUM ROLL begins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's just enough cover for Edward to remain unseen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He lands with a CLANG on the lighting catwalk above the stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He barely grabs on, disconnecting his chute just as the curtain goes up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks out at the sea of excited soldiers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Every one of them would kill him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's the legless cricket left on the anthill.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ON STAGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The curtain rises to reveal PING (27) at a microphone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's as gorgeous a woman as you'll ever see.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She stands with her hips turned in profile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her body is a knockout, dress cut to reveal skin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The soldiers are on their feet, WHISTLING and HOLLERING.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: UP ON THE CATWALK, Edward is surprised by an ENEMY SOLDIER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two men begin to SCUFFLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MUSIC starts, a vampy torch song.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ping sings melody while an off-stage voice carries perfect harmony.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes a girl can feel so alone Without a lover to call her own.
{DIALOGUE}: Sometimes it's so bad, she wants to explode.
{DIALOGUE}: Wants to grab the first man she sees and tear off his clothes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A ROAR from the soldiers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She knows what they want.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still fighting, Edward jumps for a pole on the far side of the catwalk, sliding down it to end up
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACKSTAGE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His determined opponent follows him down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But she won't.
{DIALOGUE}: No, she can't.
{DIALOGUE}: She needs a special special different unusual man.
{DIALOGUE}: Because that girl, Who looks like me, She has wants, but she has needs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{META_DATA}: (speaking)
{DIALOGUE}: Any of you got needs?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The soldiers ROAR LOUDER, STOMPING on the bleachers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Backstage, the two men are still fighting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{META_DATA}: (chorus)
{DIALOGUE}: I've had twice the adventure, Cried double the tears.
{DIALOGUE}: Two times the bad times in half the years.
{DIALOGUE}: I need a strong man, because I've got Twice the love to give.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For the first time, Ping turns, and now we see why she was standing in profile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ping is one-half of
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SIAMESE TWINS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her identical twin is JING, who's been singing harmony all this time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are two separate women who join at the waist, one set of perfect legs beneath them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward sees the twins from behind, does a double-take.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It costs him a punch to the jaw.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: Say hello, Jing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JING
{DIALOGUE}: Hello Jing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{META_DATA}: (to the crowd)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Ping.
{DIALOGUE}: She's Jing.
{DIALOGUE}: She's the good one.
{META_DATA}: (closer)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm the bad one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the MUSIC builds towards the climax, Edward finishes the fight, knocking the guard out with a right hook.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ping and Jing reach the last chorus, they strike a final pose in the shape of a heart, their arms forming the arches, their backs forming the curves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward slips behind curtains, trying to get away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The soldiers are SHOUTING for an encore, lighters waving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The curtain slowly lowers, revealing
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: EDWARD'S PARACHUTE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The APPLAUSE dies, replaced by a concerned RUMBLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Emcee yells for the Guards to search.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON STAGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ping has no idea what's happening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jing reaches into her cleavage to pull out her eyeglasses.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DRESSING ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As ARMED GUARDS search the halls below the stage, Ping and Jing shut the door to their dressing room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the closet, they start to change outfits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Off-stage, their personalities become quite apparent: Ping is brash, bitchy and ambitious, while Jing is quiet, sweet and bookish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In Chinese, subtitled...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: How could you miss your cue?
{DIALOGUE}: You make me look like a fool, out there alone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JING
{DIALOGUE}: You weren't alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ping HUFFS, turning her back on her sister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jing reaches deeper into the closet to find a new dress, exposing Edward's hiding place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She GASPS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ping turns to look.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: Who the hell are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (in Chinese)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not going to hurt you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: Damn right you're not.
{META_DATA}: (yelling)
{DIALOGUE}: GUARD!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jing grabs her, a hand over her mouth, but it's too late.
