{DIALOGUE}: What about the details?
{DIALOGUE}: How they fell in love.
{DIALOGUE}: The Circus.
{DIALOGUE}: The War.
{DIALOGUE}: You never told me any of that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: That's because most of it never happened.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: But it's romantic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (non-committal)
{DIALOGUE}: Mmm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Mmm, what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Mmm, what.
{DIALOGUE}: I know better than to argue romance with a French woman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He moves his head out from under the sheet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She follows him to the "outside."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Do you love your father?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone loves my father.
{DIALOGUE}: He's a very likeable guy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{META_DATA}: (repeating)
{DIALOGUE}: Do you love him?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will doesn't want to answer yes or no.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You have to understand.
{DIALOGUE}: When I was growing up, he was gone more than he was here.
{DIALOGUE}: And I started thinking -- maybe he has a second life somewhere else.
{DIALOGUE}: With another house, another family.
{DIALOGUE}: He leaves us, he goes to them.
{DIALOGUE}: Or maybe there is no family.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe he never wanted a family.
{DIALOGUE}: But whatever it is, maybe he likes that second life better.
{DIALOGUE}: And the reason he tells all those stories is because he can't stand this boring place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: But it's not true.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What is "true?"
{DIALOGUE}: I've never heard my father say a single true thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Off her silence...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I know why you like him.
{DIALOGUE}: I know why everyone likes him.
{DIALOGUE}: But I need you to tell me I'm not crazy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: You're not.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I need you on my side.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I am always on your side.
{DIALOGUE}: And I think you should talk to him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The family finishes eating breakfast off TV trays set up around the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For his part, Edward is looking better.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Certainly not recovered, but there's an optimism to his expression.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And for the first time, he's actually hungry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He watches as Sandra puts the cap back on the syrup.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Did I ever tell you about how...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is startled.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: The maple tree and the Buick.
{DIALOGUE}: We heard it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (re: Josephine)
{DIALOGUE}: I think someone hasn't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: The tree fell on the car, spilling the syrup, which attracted the flies, which got stuck to it and flew off with the whole car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (undeterred)
{DIALOGUE}: But the real story is how I got the car.
{DIALOGUE}: You see...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Son?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Can we talk?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra SNAPS the cap back on the syrup.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to get started on dishes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I'll help you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both women quickly gather plates.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will and Edward both smile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The women clearly want this to happen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It settles for a beat after they leave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know much about icebergs, Dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Do I?
{DIALOGUE}: I saw an iceberg once.
{DIALOGUE}: They were hauling it down to Texas for drinking water, only they didn't count on an elephant being frozen inside.
{DIALOGUE}: The woolly kind.
{DIALOGUE}: A mammoth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm trying to make a metaphor here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Then you shouldn't have started with a question.
{DIALOGUE}: Because people want to answer questions.
{DIALOGUE}: You should have started with, "The thing about icebergs is..."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (frustrated)
{DIALOGUE}: The thing about icebergs is you only see 10 percent of them.
{DIALOGUE}: The other 90 percent is below the water where you can't see it.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's what it is with you Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm only seeing this little bit that sticks above the water.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (joking)
{DIALOGUE}: What, you're seeing down to my nose?
{DIALOGUE}: My chin?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I have no idea who you are because you have never told me a single fact.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I've told you a thousand facts.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all I do, Will.
{DIALOGUE}: I tell stories.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You tell lies, Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: You tell amusing lies.
{DIALOGUE}: Stories are what you tell a five-year old at bedtime.
{DIALOGUE}: They're not elaborate mythologies you maintain when your son is ten and fifteen and twenty and thirty.
{DIALOGUE}: And the thing is, I believed you.
{DIALOGUE}: I believed your stories so much longer than I should have.
{DIALOGUE}: And then when I realized that everything you said was impossible -- everything!
{DIALOGUE}: -- I felt like such a fool to have trusted you.
{DIALOGUE}: You were like Santa Claus and the Easter Bunny combined.
{DIALOGUE}: Just as charming and just as fake.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You think I'm fake.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Only on the surface.
{DIALOGUE}: But that's all I've ever seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks away, angry and disbelieving.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, I'm about to have a kid of my own here.
{DIALOGUE}: It would kill me if he went through his whole life never understanding me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It would kill you, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want, Will?
{DIALOGUE}: Who do you want me to be?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Yourself.
{DIALOGUE}: Good, bad, everything.
{DIALOGUE}: Just show me who you are for once.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I have been nothing but myself since the day I was born.
{DIALOGUE}: And if you can't see that, it's your failing, not mine.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BACKYARD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a skimmer pole, Will cleans the leaves and debris out of the pool, but it's a fool's errand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The pool has long since gone native, a shiny slick of algae on the surface, slime covering the cemented rocks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, an underwater shape RIPPLES against the water's surface.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will is so startled that he drops the pole, which disappears into the murky water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks around, relieved that no one saw that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He casually walks away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BASEMENT STORAGE AREA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The doors open to reveal Sandra, Will and Josephine, staring into the mouth of oblivion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The storeroom is a museum of hasty decisions and half-finished projects: partially built outboard motors, dead bonsai trees, Frankensteinian lawnmowers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We also find boxes of products Edward used to sell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clearing a path, Sandra leads Will to a roll-top desk, its ribs covered in dust.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two beaten metal file cabinets sit beside it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Your father decided he needed to have an office, and it wouldn't do to have it in the house.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll know better than me what's important.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With some effort, Will forces up the desktop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a HISS, a neighbor's cat makes a run for it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will's getting used to being startled.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BASEMENT STORAGE AREA - DAY [LATER]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will, Sandra and Josephine have worked through two trash bags of papers to throw out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking through a new file, Sandra makes a small sound.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A memory.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra hands Will a yellowed telegram.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shares it with Josephine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: It was during the war.
{DIALOGUE}: Your father went missing.
{DIALOGUE}: They thought he was dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will can't believe what he's reading.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: That really happened?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Not everything your father says is a complete fabrication.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then Sandra stands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to check on him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I need to lie down for a bit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine kisses him, then follows Sandra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will re-reads the telegram, still bewildered.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking for a place to put it, he tucks it into a strange mechanical hand on the desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It clamps down automatically.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will smiles, a memory.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hasn't thought about this device in years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We slowly PUSH IN on the telegram, held in the hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward's VOICE begins as a memory...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: After the war, the sons of Alabama returned home, looking for work.
{DIALOGUE}: Each had an advantage over me.
{DIALOGUE}: They were alive, while I was -- officially -- deceased.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DOWNTOWN OFFICE - DAY [STORY]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward shakes hands with his new boss, a TOUPEED MAN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The company is called "Confederated Products."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The OFFICE LADIES all love Edward.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: With my prospects few, I took a job as a travelling salesman.
{DIALOGUE}: It suited me.
{DIALOGUE}: If there's one thing you can say about Edward Bloom, it's that I am a social person.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COUNTY FAIR - DAY [STORY]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On a low platform, Edward pitches a brilliant new product to the crowd.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I've travelled from Tennessee to Timbuktu, and if there's one thing people have in common, is we could all use a hand around the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward sets down a contraption, which looks something like a metal lava lamp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Like a flower, it unfolds to reveal five fingers and a thumb.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the Hand Around the House.
{META_DATA}: (TM)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Why, with this product you can...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: QUICK MONTAGE as he demonstrates:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Open a jar.
{DIALOGUE}: Open a letter.
{DIALOGUE}: Scratch yourself while wearing mittens.
{DIALOGUE}: Hold a book.
{DIALOGUE}: Hold a baby.
{DIALOGUE}: Hold the dog away from kittens.
{DIALOGUE}: It's strong enough, you can do a handstand with no hands at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Indeed, a remarkably agile Edward is able to support his entire weight on it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd APPLAUDS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You can use it to point out important information.
{DIALOGUE}: Or dangers.
{DIALOGUE}: Or beautiful women.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hand points a finger at an HEAVYSET MAN IN OVERALLS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: We're still working on that one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd LAUGHS.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. A COUNTRY ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward drives, his hand out in the wind.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Soon I added other products, and other cities, until my territory stretched from the coast to western Texas.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TRAILER PARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward kisses his pregnant wife goodbye, as much in love as ever.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I could be gone for weeks at a time.
{DIALOGUE}: But every other Friday, I'd put all the money I'd made into an account set aside for a proper house with a white picket fence.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HORIZON SAVINGS & LOAN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Establishing this Texas institution, we come...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HORIZON SAVINGS & LOAN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bank is busy with the lunch-hour crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Taking his place in line, Edward fills out a deposit slip.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the line snakes around through the ropes, the man in front of him gets a look at Edward.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: THE MAN
{DIALOGUE}: Edward?
{DIALOGUE}: Edward Bloom?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The man is none other than...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: It's me.
{DIALOGUE}: Norther Winslow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I was astonished to see the greatest poet of both Ashton and Spectre all the way out in Texas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men shake, disbelieving this lucky coincidence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I don't believe it!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: I want you to know, when you left Spectre it opened my eyes.
{DIALOGUE}: There was a whole life out there that I was not living.
{DIALOGUE}: So I travelled.
{DIALOGUE}: I saw France, and Africa, half of South America.
{DIALOGUE}: Every day a new adventure, that's my motto.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: That's great, Norther.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm happy for you.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't believe I helped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's genuinely proud.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: So what are you up to now?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: I'm robbing this place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the front of the line, Norther pulls two pistols out of his coat, FIRING both into the ceiling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SCREAMS all around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The skinny SECURITY GUARD makes a halfhearted reach for his gun, but Norther waves him off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The guard takes out his gun and slides it over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{META_DATA}: (to Edward)
{DIALOGUE}: Would you mind grabbing that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's nothing threatening about his delivery -- he might as well be asking for a Budweiser.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, Edward senses it would be best to do as he says.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes the guard's gun.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{META_DATA}: (to the crowd)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I want all of you to lie down.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna be cleaning out the cash drawers, and my associate here is going to handle the vault.
{META_DATA}: (pointing to a Teller Woman)
{DIALOGUE}: You help my friend, okay?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The TELLER WOMAN nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Edward, not sure what to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has a gun, but he truly doesn't want to shoot Norther.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Teller Woman is already waving him to the back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He decides he better go.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AT THE VAULT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Teller Woman is crying as she works the combination.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward feels horrible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I'm really sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I just don't want anybody to get hurt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER WOMAN
{DIALOGUE}: It's not that, it's just...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She pulls open the vault door.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. THE VAULT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The inner sanctum of the Horizon Savings and Loan holds exactly one folding chair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nothing else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER WOMAN
{DIALOGUE}: ...there's no money.
{DIALOGUE}: We're completely bankrupt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It turned out the savings and loan had already been robbed -- not by armed bandits, but by speculators in Texas real estate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER WOMAN
{META_DATA}: (dead serious)
{DIALOGUE}: You gotta promise you won't tell anybody.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EDWARD'S CAR - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward drives the getaway car, though truthfully they're going just a little over the speed limit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one's following them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's an empty country road for miles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Norther HOLLERS with body-tingling joy as he counts the money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Sixty.
{DIALOGUE}: Eighty.
{DIALOGUE}: Four hundred dollars!
{DIALOGUE}: Not bad for just the drawers.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's see what you got from the vault.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward winces, but doesn't say anything yet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Digging through the vault bag, Norther is surprised to find only a single deposit envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rips it open, revealing just a little cash inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even some dimes and pennies.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: This is it?
{DIALOGUE}: The whole vault.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: 'Fraid so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Edward, it's got your deposit slip on it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caught, Edward has to confess...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I just didn't want you to go empty-handed.
{DIALOGUE}: There's something you should know, Norther.
{DIALOGUE}: You see, the reason why...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward continues his narration...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I told Norther about the vagaries of Texas oil money and its effect on real estate prices, and how lax enforcement of fiduciary process had made savings and loans particularly vulnerable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hearing this news, Norther was left with one conclusion:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TEXAS ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Norther leans in the driver's side window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: I should go to Wall Street.
{DIALOGUE}: That's where all the money is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks over at Norther, the reality sinking in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I knew then that while my days as a criminal were over, Norther's were just beginning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two men wave at each other as Edward drives off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the last moment, Norther calls out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NORTHER WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Edward, thank you for the hand!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's talking about his Hand Around the House.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HOLD ON Norther for a beat, dreaming of his future.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When Norther made his first million dollars, he sent me a check for ten thousand.
{DIALOGUE}: I protested, but he said it was my fee as his career advisor.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BLOOM HOUSE [MID/LATE '70'S] - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra is watering the garden.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will (5) runs past her to greet Edward, just returned from another trip.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Ten thousand dollars is no fortune to most men.
{DIALOGUE}: But it was enough to buy my wife a proper house with a white picket fence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We reveal the Bloom house, the nicest one in the neighborhood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward kisses his wife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And for that, it was all the riches a man could ever want.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra drops the hose, letting it run on the lawn.
{META_DATA}: TRANSITION TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE BATHROOM - DAY [PRESENT]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON Edward's hand as he turns knobs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON water SPLASHING into the claw-foot bathtub, which begins to fill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still wearing his pajamas, Edward climbs into the tub.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carefully lowers himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the water reaches the third button up on his pajama shirt, Edward suddenly slides
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: UNDERWATER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bubbles rise from his nose for a few beats, then stop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's quiet, except for the distant SPLASHING of water from the spigot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward's eyes are closed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then the SPLASHING water goes silent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward opens one eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits up to find
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SANDRA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: sitting on the edge of the tub.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She doesn't seem particularly worried -- her husband has always done this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I was drying out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I see.
{DIALOGUE}: We need to get you one of those plant misters.
{DIALOGUE}: We can spray you like a fern.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles, then pulls his knees up, making room for her in the tub.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat while she considers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra steps out of her sandals and climbs into the tub, facing him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her dress is soaked, but she doesn't mind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans forward and kisses her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When they separate, she has tears hanging in her eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Come now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wipes them away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I don't think I'll ever dry out.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BASEMENT STORAGE AREA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Perched awkwardly on a canoe, Will's made it through another file cabinet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes through the folders page by page, but usually ends up tossing the whole thing in the trash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's about to toss a file when he stops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Takes another look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something doesn't make sense.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE / STAIRS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will is headed upstairs when his mother comes around the corner with an armful of laundry, including her wet dress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Is he awake?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: He just fell asleep.
{DIALOGUE}: Josephine's with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She passes him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Mom?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will quickly debates whether or not to ask her...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Did you and Dad have any other property?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (thinking)
{DIALOGUE}: I suppose your grandmother's house when she passed on.
{DIALOGUE}: But we sold that right away.
{DIALOGUE}: Your cousin Shirley bought it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: So you never bought any land.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Heavens no.
{DIALOGUE}: We had a hard enough time keeping the mortgage on this place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will nods, just curious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He continues heading up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILL AND JOSEPHINE'S ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will changes his shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Takes his keys off the nightstand.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COUNTY ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will's rental car drives past a sign reading, "Ashton, 10 miles."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILL'S CAR - DAY / DRIVING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will checks the address on one of his father's files.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ASHTON GAS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will talks to the ATTENDANT, who points him in a direction, then gestures a series of left, right, left, rights.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will drives down a road that seems somewhat familiar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then we realize why: a roadsign reads "Welcome to Spectre!"
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. A LONE HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting at the edge of a swamp, the little two-story feels lonely, set deep in its lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dapples of light break through the trees, a light breeze swaying the branches.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Will walks from the car, the WHIRR of cicadas grows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He checks the number: 33.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is surrounded by a white square-picket fence, identical to his mother's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will notices this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching the porch, we hear a PIANO playing inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Badly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Re-checking the number on a form he's carrying, Will KNOCKS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The piano stops.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WOMAN'S VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Go back to the start.
{DIALOGUE}: Right hand only.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The piano starts again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FOOTSTEPS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens to reveal a blonde woman in her 50's -- the woman from the grocery store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her name is Jenny Hill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She and Will are startled to see each other.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I wasn't expecting you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Confused, Will checks the name on the form.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Are you Jenny Hill?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{DIALOGUE}: And you're Will.
{DIALOGUE}: I've seen your picture, that's how I recognize you.
{DIALOGUE}: I almost said something at the store, but it would have been awkward.
{META_DATA}: (a beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Like this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The PIANO STUDENT, a black boy of eight, has stopped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's watching the conversation at the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Speaking of awkward...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{META_DATA}: (to the student)
{DIALOGUE}: Listen, Kenny.
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't we skip the lesson today?
{DIALOGUE}: We can go again next week.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands him five dollars out of her pocket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STUDENT
{DIALOGUE}: Do I have to give it back to my Mom?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I won't tell her if you won't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: You don't have to tell him twice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's out the door in a flash.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. JENNY'S KITCHEN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While Will sips his iced tea, Jenny flips through a form she never expected to see again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands it back to Will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How did you know my father?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: This was on his sales route, so he was through here all the time.
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone in town knew him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not flinching...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Were you and my father having an affair?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{META_DATA}: (taken aback)
{DIALOGUE}: Wow.
{DIALOGUE}: Wow, you just said it.
{DIALOGUE}: I was expecting to dance around this for another half hour.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I've seen him with women.
{DIALOGUE}: He flirts.
{DIALOGUE}: He always has.
{DIALOGUE}: On some level, I presumed he was cheating on my mother.
{DIALOGUE}: I just never had proof.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She moves, trying to get out of the corner he's boxed her into.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once she's finally free...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Can I ask you a question?
{DIALOGUE}: Why did you come here today?
{DIALOGUE}: If you found this deed, why didn't you just ask Eddie?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Because he's dying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny is taken back by the suddenness of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's a tangle of conflicting emotions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I don't know how much you want to know about any of this.
{DIALOGUE}: You have one image of your father and it would be wrong for me to go and change it.
{DIALOGUE}: Especially this late in the game.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: My father talked about a lot of things he never did, and I'm sure he did a lot of things he never talked about.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just trying to reconcile the two.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fair enough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny takes a seat across from him at the table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: The first thing you have to understand, is that your father never meant to end up here.
{DIALOGUE}: And yet he did, twice.
{DIALOGUE}: The first time, he was early.
{DIALOGUE}: The second time, he was late.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EDWARD'S CAR / DRIVING - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's late, and Edward is pensive.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Those days, your father was working for himself.
{DIALOGUE}: If there was one thing you could say about Edward Bloom, it's that he was a social person, and people took a liking to him.
{DIALOGUE}: One night he was returning from three weeks on the road, when he hit a thunderstorm unlike any in his life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The first raindrops hit the windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward turns on the wipers.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EDWARD'S CAR - NIGHT - [THE STORM]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, a deluge descends.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not even rain anymore -- there's no space between the drops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's like being caught in a waterfall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's that loud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No choice, Edward stops the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Puts on the handbrake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just as suddenly, the sound changes -- no longer pounding, but softly SPLASHING.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The world is close and echoing, because --
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EDWARD'S CAR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -- the car is underwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tires are still on the road, but where there used to be air is water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Three catfish swim in front of his headlights.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. THE CAR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Realizing his plight, Edward tries to remain calm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Water is trickling in through the crack between the window and the door, but very slowly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For now, he's fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That's when he sees her -- The Girl in the River.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's swimming outside the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While we never see her face exactly, she remains just as beautiful, just as mysterious, as the first time we saw her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She puts her hand to the windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He puts his up to meet hers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And smiles.
{META_DATA}: FLASH CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD BY DIRT ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's morning, and the sun shines brightly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Birds CHIRP.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trees drip and the grass shines, still wet from last night's rain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward gathers the clothes that have spilled out of his suitcase, which broke open when he dropped it from
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HIS CAR,
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: which balances precariously ten feet up in an elm tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Edward gathers his last pair of socks, he notices a shiny piece of metal sticking out of the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls it out, rubs it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a key.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the Key to the City he lost years ago.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Fate has a way of circling back on a man, and taking him by surprise.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carrying his busted suitcase, a tired Edward walks toward a one-street town in the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We pass a rusty sign...
{META_DATA}: "Welcome to Spectre."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MAIN STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amazed and disbelieving, Edward walks down the center of the road, no cars coming from either direction.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks up to find his faded shoes still dangling from the power line, along with the rest of the town's.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A man sees things differently at different times in his life.
{DIALOGUE}: This town didn't seem the same now that he was older.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TOWN OF SPECTRE - VARIOUS SHOTS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We look around the town, on and off Main Street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are "FOR SALE" signs in many of the windows
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A new road had brought the outside world to Spectre, and with it, banks, liens and debt.
{DIALOGUE}: Almost everywhere you looked, people were bankrupt.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SPECTRE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We slowly MOVE THROUGH a foreclosure auction to find Edward watching.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two very corporate MEN IN SUITS, stick out among the bidders.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Two different corporations were looking at buying the town, if they could get the price low enough.
{DIALOGUE}: One wanted to open a chicken processing plant.
{DIALOGUE}: The other, a municipal dump.
{DIALOGUE}: Either way, Spectre would be destroyed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward raises his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Fifty-thousand!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everyone turns to look at this new bidder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And so Edward Bloom decided to buy the town, in order to save it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHER WINSLOW'S MANHATTAN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward pitches his plan to Norther.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He was never a wealthy man, but he had made other men rich, and now he asked for their favors.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT./EXT. VARIOUS LOCATIONS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS SHOTS: Expressive and passionate as always, Edward talks to Ping, Jing and Amos Calloway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Most of them had never seen Spectre -- they only had Edward's words to describe it.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all they needed.
{DIALOGUE}: He sold them on the dream.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JING
{DIALOGUE}: You can structure it as a historical trust.
{DIALOGUE}: But you'll need every contiguous piece of property.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all or nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Edward takes notes...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: So first he bought the farms.
{DIALOGUE}: Then he bought the houses.
{DIALOGUE}: Then he bought the stores.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. AL'S COUNTRY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finishing up with AL, Edward shakes hands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever he bought, the people were not asked to leave or pay rent or anything.
{DIALOGUE}: They were just asked to keep doing as they were doing.
{DIALOGUE}: In that way, he could make sure the town would never die.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD IN THE SWAMP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward climbs out of his car, the road having literally stopped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is shining, but it can barely penetrate the trees' thick canopy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Within six months, his trust had purchased the entire town.
{DIALOGUE}: With one exception.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, he sees a shack, so old it's nearly fallen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks toward it, the marshy ground SQUISHING up around his feet, soaking the hems of his trousers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear a PIANO playing from inside the shack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward KNOCKS on the half-hung door, which swings open by itself.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The inside is nicer than you'd think, a real home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fire burns in the stove, and curtains hang in the windows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With her back turned to him, Jenny Hill plays the piano.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward doesn't recognize her as the little girl who used to have a crush on him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Without turning, she says...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: You must be Edward Bloom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: How did you know?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She keeps PLAYING.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: No one would come out here unless they had business.
{DIALOGUE}: And no one would have business with me except for you.
{DIALOGUE}: You're buying the town.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Apparently I've overlooked this one piece of it, and I'd like to remedy that.
{DIALOGUE}: You see, in order for the town to be preserved, the trust must own it in its entirety.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: So I've heard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'll offer you more than it's worth.
{DIALOGUE}: And you know you won't have to move.
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing will change except the name on the deed, you have my word.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny stops playing, her piece not quite finished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She turns to face him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward still doesn't recognize her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Now let me get this straight.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll buy the swamp from me, but I'll stay in it.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll own the house, but it'll still be mine.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be here, and you'll come and go as you please to one place or another.
{DIALOGUE}: Do I have that right?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Strange to hear it put that way, but --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: In so many words, yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Then I don't think so Mr. Bloom.
{DIALOGUE}: If nothing is going to change, I'd just as soon it not change in the way it hasn't been changing all this time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: It's not like you're going to lose anything.
{DIALOGUE}: You can ask anyone in town.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been nothing if not generous.
{DIALOGUE}: I want the best for everyone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Bloom, why are you buying this land?
{DIALOGUE}: Some sort of midlife crisis?
{DIALOGUE}: Instead of buying a convertible, you buy a town?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at her, puzzled and surprised.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one has really asked before.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Helping people makes me happy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not convinced you should be happy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: Have I offended you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She finally turns to face him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: No, you did exactly what you promised.
{DIALOGUE}: You came back.
{DIALOGUE}: I was just expecting you sooner.
{META_DATA}: FLASHBACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SPECTRE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Jenny Hill watches barefoot Edward leave Spectre for the first time.
{META_DATA}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally realizing who this woman is...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: You're Beamen's daughter.
{DIALOGUE}: Your last name is different.
{META_DATA}: (realizing)
{DIALOGUE}: You married.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I was 18.
{DIALOGUE}: He was 28.
{DIALOGUE}: Turns out that was a big difference.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before he can say anything more...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I won't be selling you this house, Mr. Bloom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I see.
{DIALOGUE}: I thank you for your time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bit bewildered, Edward tips his hat to her as he leaves.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT/INT. SWAMP SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward pulls the door shut behind him as he leaves, but it breaks off in his hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not the clean exit he was hoping for.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside Jenny looks out, surprised and annoyed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward tries to lift the door back on the hinges, but they SNAP off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door frame buckles and the whole shack CREAKS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to lean the door against the frame, but it keeps slipping.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: It's okay, just leave it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I can get it.
{DIALOGUE}: I can just...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans the door a different way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It holds for a beat then falls in, SMASHING a small table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Lord, I'm sorry I..
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Please.
{DIALOGUE}: Go.
{DIALOGUE}: Just go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'll...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's dead serious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Weighing the scales of chivalry, he finally backs away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Turns and heads back towards his car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We STAY ON Jenny, watching him go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's furious, but there's something more in her feelings for him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something softer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Most men in that situation would accept their failure and move on.
{DIALOGUE}: But Edward was not like most men.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SWAMP SHACK ROAD - ANOTHER DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With Karl the Giant's help, Edward unloads a brand new door from a pickup truck.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While Jenny watches, half-annoyed, half-amused, Edward tries to set the door square.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl pushes against the side of the house until it fits.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SHACK - ANOTHER DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holding nails between his lips, Edward puts in new windows himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny is making soup, laughing at the story he's telling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As the months passed, he found more and more things to fix, until the shack no longer resembled itself.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SWAMP - ANOTHER DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward and Karl cut down a tree, letting in a flood of light.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the golden pollen hanging in the air, we RISE UP to see the shack is now
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE LOVELY HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: we saw before.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's tiny and white, with black shutters and a steep roof.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A white picket fence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In every detail it is impossibly charming.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. JENNY'S HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward is screwing a hat rack into the wall in the foyer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny leans against the doorframe listening to his story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And watching him with deepest affection.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Of course, the best part was creating new material.
{DIALOGUE}: By the time the twins and I got to Havana, we had a whole new routine worked out for them, with just a ukulele and a harmonica.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finished with his work, he takes his hat off the chair and hangs it on the rack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Perfect.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A look between them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With that last job done, there's no reason for him to be staying any longer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I suppose I should...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes his hat off the rack.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: You can leave it there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Does she really mean it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She comes closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward holds his ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes his hand, lifting his hat up to the peg.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's very close -- just a half-inch from kissing him when --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -- Edward gently holds her back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She freezes, stunned and humiliated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She pulls away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Don't.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't be embarrassed.
{DIALOGUE}: I should never have let you think that...
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I am in love with my wife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: And from the moment I saw her until the moment I die, she's the only one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Lucky girl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry, Jenny.
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With that, he begins to leaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Wait!
{DIALOGUE}: Edward!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She finds a pen and hastily signs the deed to the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hands it to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a look, he thanks her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then goes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SPECTRE - MAGIC HOUR
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward takes a final look at this perfect little town.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: One day, Edward Bloom left, and never returned to the town he'd saved.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs in his car and starts the engine.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. JENNY HILL'S HOUSE - DAY TO NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we watch, the swamp begins to overtake the house, swallowing it in a tangle of vines and mossy branches.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shoots burst up through the planks in the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Snakes slither through the marsh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Day becomes night.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As for the girl, the common belief was that she'd become a witch, and crazy at that.
{DIALOGUE}: She became something of a legend herself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We REVERSE to find FOUR KIDS looking in through the rusty iron gate with flashlights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then they run away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And the story ended where it began.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. JENNY HILL'S KITCHEN - PRESENT DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will and Jenny are still sitting at her table, a pitcher of iced tea between them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Logically, you couldn't be the Witch, because she was old back when he was young.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: No, it's logical if you think like your father.
{DIALOGUE}: See, to him, there's only two women: your mother and everyone else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't become crazy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, therapy.
{DIALOGUE}: And one day I realized I was in love with a man who could never love me back.
{DIALOGUE}: I was living in a fairy tale.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will smiles to hear it called that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: People aren't like they are in stories.
{DIALOGUE}: They hurt each other without meaning to.
{DIALOGUE}: They are kind and unbelievably cruel at the same moment.
{DIALOGUE}: Like me, now.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not sure I should have told you any of this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her composure is starting to break.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: No, I wanted to know.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm glad I know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat, both staring at their iced tea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny is working herself into more of a state by not talking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I wanted to meet you for the longest time.
{DIALOGUE}: I did.
{META_DATA}: (a smile)
{DIALOGUE}: I envied you so much.
{DIALOGUE}: The way Eddie would talk about you when you were at Missouri, that award you won.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations, incidentally.
{DIALOGUE}: And when you got the job at the A.P., everything, he was so proud of you.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, that's the thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Every moment he loved you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's fighting tears, not the first ones she's shed over this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: And as brightly as the sun would shine when he was with me, every time he left it disappeared.
{DIALOGUE}: I wanted to be as important to him as you were, and I was never going to be.
{DIALOGUE}: I was make-believe and his other life, you, were real.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON Will, sorting through his swirling thoughts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JENNY
{DIALOGUE}: You knew that, didn't you?
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILL'S CAR - DAY / DRIVING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will skips through the stations on the radio, but ultimately turns it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's trying to think.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BLOOM HOUSE - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will walks up the front steps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a subtle change to his expression, a dark cloud lifted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He unlocks the door.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BLOOM HOUSE FOYER - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's half-dark and quiet in the house, no talking, no TV.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will sets his keys on the table.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. KITCHEN - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will looks in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Empty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (calling out)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{DIALOGUE}: Mom?
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. UPSTAIRS HALLWAY - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow Will, looking into his and Josephine's room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He aims for the guest room at the end of the hall.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST ROOM - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking over his shoulder, we see his father's bed is empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sheets are in a tangle on the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then Will half-runs back down the hall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Back down the stairs.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FOYER - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Headed out, Will grabs his keys off the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LOOK RIGHT, where the "MESSAGE" light blinks on the answering machine.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ENTRANCE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hospital is so new, it's not even finished -- thick plastic hangs from exposed framing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's no one at the information desk, so Will forges ahead.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL HALLWAY - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will reads a directory board, trying to decide the best place to start.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, behind him --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Will!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to see his wife at a payphone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hangs up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She was calling him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What happened?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Your father had a stroke.
{DIALOGUE}: He's upstairs with your mom and Dr. Bennett.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Is he going to be okay?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: How can she answer?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He half-smiles, realizing the idiocy of his question.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Of course his father's not going to be okay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What I mean is, will he get back to the way he was when...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She cuts him off --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: He won't.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And like that, it's done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HOLD ON Will, reeling from the news.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward sleeps peacefully, just an oxygen tube under his nose.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are no beeping monitors, no blinking lights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's mercifully quiet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra squeezes Will's hand tightly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's holding herself together, but it's been a tough day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Bennett has just gone through the details for the third time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I don't suppose one of us could stay with him.
{DIALOGUE}: In case he...
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: In case he wakes up, one of us should be there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I'll stay.
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you go home with Josephine and I'll stay tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (to Dr. Bennett)
{DIALOGUE}: That's okay?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: It's fine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{META_DATA}: (to Will)
{DIALOGUE}: You'll call if...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I will.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll call.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Mom, do you want some time with Dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A nod, then Will holds the door for Dr. Bennett and Josephine as they leave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra is alone in the room with her husband.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She neatens his hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holds his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she kisses his fingers, she tweaks her chin with them -- his signature move.
{META_DATA}: TRANSITION TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL HALLWAY - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra waits outside the women's restroom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her face is a study in strained composure -- acknowledging the inevitable but refusing to surrender to it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine emerges.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: It seems every hour I have to...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: It was the same when I was carrying Will.
{DIALOGUE}: Like clockwork.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two women start to walk, no hurry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: Do you like it, being pregnant?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: I do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I loved it.
{DIALOGUE}: It sounds peculiar, but I loved every minute of it.
{DIALOGUE}: I did.
{DIALOGUE}: Eddie was travelling a lot, so he was gone, but I felt like I always had a piece of him with me.
{DIALOGUE}: A little part of his soul inside me.
{DIALOGUE}: I could feel it.
{DIALOGUE}: It was alive and kicking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra has accidentally evoked a storm of emotion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She struggles to keep it in check.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost a whisper...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SANDRA
{DIALOGUE}: I really miss that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a few breaths, Sandra tries to hold on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hold back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOSEPHINE
{DIALOGUE}: Don't stop.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then Sandra finally melts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine holds her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two women stand together in the hallway, letting the moment be.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will sits in a chair beside the bed, working through the crossword puzzle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A KNOCK as Dr. Bennett enters with his overcoat and bag, ready to leave for the night.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Glad to see you're not trying to have a heartfelt talk.
{DIALOGUE}: It's one of my greatest annoyances, when people talk to those who can't hear them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: My father and I have an advantage.
{DIALOGUE}: We never talk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Bennett smiles as he checks Edward's chart.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How long have you known my father?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Thirty years.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe more.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How would you describe him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{META_DATA}: (re: chart)
{DIALOGUE}: Five-eleven.
{DIALOGUE}: One-eighty.
{DIALOGUE}: Regulated hypertension.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: How would his son describe him?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tables turned, Will searches for an answer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He doesn't have one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dr. Bennett hangs the chart back on the bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Did your father ever tell you about the day you were born?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: A thousand times.
{DIALOGUE}: He caught an uncatchable fish.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Not that one.
{DIALOGUE}: The real story.
{DIALOGUE}: Did he ever tell you that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (suddenly interested)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother came in about three in the afternoon.
{DIALOGUE}: Her neighbor drove her, on account of your father was on business in Wichita.
{DIALOGUE}: You were born a week early, but there were no complications.
{DIALOGUE}: It was a perfect delivery.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, your father was sorry to miss it, but it wasn't the custom for the men to be in the room for deliveries then, so I can't see as it would have been much different had he been there.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's the real story of how you were born.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long silence, just the sounds of the hospital, doctors being paged.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Not very exciting, is it?
{DIALOGUE}: And I suppose if I had to choose between the true version and an elaborate one involving a fish and a wedding ring, I might choose the fancy version.
{DIALOGUE}: But that's just me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will half-smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patting Will's shoulder, Dr. Bennett leaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We STAY ON Will and his father for a long time, then Will takes his pen and starts making a list.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - VARIOUS SHOTS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will flips to a new page.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The list keeps getting longer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles, remembering something.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On his fourth page, he looks up at his motionless father.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat, then we slowly
{META_DATA}: CROSSFADE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - PRE-DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's very early morning, and the first blue light of day is glowing through the vertical blinds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still in his chair, Will wakes up a bit at a time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The notepad is on his lap, the pen in his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He cracks his neck, crooked from sleeping on it wrong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What woke him up?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks to his right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holds his gaze for a breath.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His father is awake, silently GASPING for breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes are open, scared and confused.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad!
{DIALOGUE}: Do you want me to get a nurse?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward shakes his head unambiguously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will already has his finger on the orange "nurse call" button, but doesn't push it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: What can I do?
{DIALOGUE}: Can I help?
{DIALOGUE}: Can I get you something?
{DIALOGUE}: Water?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will pours a glass from the pitcher on the nightstand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He holds it to his father's lips, but Edward won't drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pushes it away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wanted something else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (whispering)
{DIALOGUE}: The river.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: The river?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It takes Edward all his strength to put together each thought.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's like he's only half-there, fighting to hang on to this world.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me how it happens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: How what happens?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: How I go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON WILL, realizing...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You mean what you saw in The Eye?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Yes, that's what he was trying to say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know that story, Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: You never told me that one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will pushes his fingers under his father's heavy hand, and holds it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's nothing else to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward looks around, confused and increasingly scared.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees the end approaching, but doesn't know exactly what's coming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Without the story, he's lost.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fighting the urge to panic --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I can try, Dad.
{DIALOGUE}: If you help.
{DIALOGUE}: Just tell me how it starts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Like this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will looks around the room, increasingly desperate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks to the nurse call button.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He really wants to press it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON EDWARD, waiting for Will to begin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: It's morning, and you and I are in the hospital.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd fallen asleep in the chair.
{DIALOGUE}: I wake up and I see you, and...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - DAY [STORY VERSION]
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's dawn, and the first golden glow is shining through the vertical blinds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (louder and concerned)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We LOOK OVER to find a nimble Edward sitting up in bed, combing his hair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Let's get out of here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Somehow, you're better.
{DIALOGUE}: Different.
{DIALOGUE}: You're getting ready to go.
{DIALOGUE}: And I say...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, you're in no condition to...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Edward throws back the covers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: There's a fold-up wheelchair in the bathroom.
{DIALOGUE}: Wrap a blanket around me.
{DIALOGUE}: As soon as we get off this floor, we'll be in the clear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will heads for the bathroom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sure enough, the wheelchair is there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry!
{DIALOGUE}: We don't have much time.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the blanket draped over his head like a ghost, Edward points for his son to steer the wheelchair thataway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Faster!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They pass a HEAVYSET NURSE, who turns to look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rounding a corner, they nearly crash into Dr. Bennett.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DR. BENNETT
{DIALOGUE}: Will!
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: What are you doing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before he can answer, Will spots Edward rolling the chair himself, pumping both arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will dashes to catch up with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Heavyset Nurse leans out of Edward's hospital room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NURSE
{DIALOGUE}: Security!
{DIALOGUE}: Stop them!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DOWN THE HALL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the elevators, Sandra and Josephine step out to find Will and Edward barreling straight at them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: No time to explain!
{DIALOGUE}: Follow us!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seeing SECURITY GUARDS heading their way, a quick-thinking Sandra shoves a nearby cart into them, bowling them down.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ELEVATOR - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will brakes hard, sliding with both feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The chair nearly crashes into the back wall as the doors close.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PARKING LOT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will races Edward down the row, finally reaching the Chevrolet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: AT THE CAR
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will lifts his father out of the chair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I pick you up and you hardly weigh anything.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't explain it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will sets him in the passenger seat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Water.
{DIALOGUE}: I need water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scrambling in back, Will finds a liter of Arrowhead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hands it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward unscrews the cap, but instead of drinking it, he douses himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Soaks the blanket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will pops the trunk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Starts to fold up the wheelchair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Leave it!
{DIALOGUE}: We won't need it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIRES SMOKE as the car peals out.
{META_DATA}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - DAY [REALITY]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIGHT ON Will, trying to hold back tears as he talks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: And we have to take Glenville to avoid all the church traffic, because those damn church people drive too slow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIGHT ON Edward, enjoying that detail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's focused completely on Will's story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: I ask...
{META_DATA}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GLENVILLE BLVD. - DAY [STORY VERSION]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chevy slaloms through the Sunday-morning traffic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Where are we headed?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: You say...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CHEVY - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: The River!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will stops short, the traffic backed up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He HONKS, trying to get around the jam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But it's no use.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, up ahead, the cars start moving, shoved aside by massive hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Karl the Giant, clearing a path by brute force.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward leans out the window and waves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl waves back.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ASHTON RIVER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same stretch of the river where it all began.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CROWD of more than 100 waiting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As we get closer to the river, we see everybody's already there.
{DIALOGUE}: And I mean everybody.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amos Calloway is here with the circus folk, including Mr. Soggybottom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We also find Edward's Mother and Father, the Mayor, and many others from along the way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No one has aged a day since we saw them last.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While Ping scans the horizon, Jing nuzzles with her boyfriend, Norther Winslow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Ping who first spots the Chevrolet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PING
{DIALOGUE}: He's here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd CHEERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Ashton marching band PLAYS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jenny Hill smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: So does the Old Woman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PUSH IN on the Old Woman's glass eye, where we see...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: YOUNG EDWARD
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: reflected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is what he saw.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. THE CHEVROLET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amazed, Will turns to his father.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: It's unbelievable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Story of my life.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVERSIDE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will gets out of the Chevrolet, overwhelmed by the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind him, Sandra, Josephine and Dr. Bennett pull up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Karl comes just after that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Crossing to the passenger side, Will lifts his father out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Strangely, he's gotten even lighter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will carries him easily.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward pulls off his shoes, tying the laces together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands them to Josephine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She throws them up at the powerline.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They loop over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: APPLAUSE and CHEERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd parts to let Will and Edward get to the river.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he passes, Edward shakes some hands, pats some people on the cheek, and gives others a good poke in the ribs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And the strange thing is, there's not a sad face to be found.
{DIALOGUE}: Everyone's just so glad to see you, and send you off right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will walks into the river, up to his knees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns back so his father can face the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward waves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye everybody!
{DIALOGUE}: Farewell!
{DIALOGUE}: Adieu!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: THE CROWD (VARIOUS)
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye Edward!
{DIALOGUE}: / See ya!
{DIALOGUE}: / We'll miss you!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But one face is missing from the crowd -- Sandra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will turns to see she's already standing in the river beside them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The reflection of the light off the water gives Sandra an unearthly glow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's more tranquil and more beautiful than we've ever seen her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: My girl in the river.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She kisses him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tweaks her chin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd HOLLERS in approval, but their moment remains strangely private.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only Will is there to witness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the kiss ends, Edward tries to pull off his wedding ring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But it's stuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally, he sucks on it, pulling it free with his teeth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A look to Will, a smile with a glint of gold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will takes the ring out of his mouth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward suddenly drops out of Will's arms with a SPLASH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For he's no longer a man, but rather
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A FAT CATFISH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: swimming at his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We watch as the catfish circles, then heads for deeper water, disappearing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will and his mother stand knee-deep in the water, watching Edward Bloom swim away into the sunlight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine is back on the shore, along with the entire crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MUSIC BUILDS to a climax, then...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Down the river, a GIANT FISH suddenly jumps out of the water, cutting a beautiful arc across the sunset.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It then dives back under with a SPLASH.
{META_DATA}: CROSSFADE BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will has tears hanging in the corners of his eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: You become what you always were.
{DIALOGUE}: A very big fish.
{META_DATA}: (he smiles)
{DIALOGUE}: And that's the way it happens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{META_DATA}: (a whisper)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Exactly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Edward smiles, proud of both of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes are so pale and so open, we can almost see his soul.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In every atom of his body, in every thought, Edward Bloom is entirely happy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And this is how he goes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL HALLWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will shuts the door to his father's room behind him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The walk to the payphones seems to take a lifetime.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finds a quarter, starts to dial.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has to squint to see through the water in his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's ringing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And ringing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The other end answers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{META_DATA}: (voice cracking)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That's all he can get out before the dam breaks inside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He presses closer to the phone, trying to shield himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MUSIC begins that will carry us through the next passage.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOSPITAL RECEPTION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will waits at reception as Sandra and Josephine come off the elevator.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GUEST ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine opens the curtains, letting white sunlight in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She strips the bed.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BEDROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will and his mother pick out one of Edward's ties, for Will to wear at the funeral.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will tries to button the cuffs on the shirt he borrowed, but they're the kind that need links.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes through the top drawer of the dresser, trying to find a matching pair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Further down, he finds a ribbon tied to
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE KEY TO THE CITY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles, disbelieving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a real thing.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CEMETERY / ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will helps his mother out of a black sedan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's well- composed, not nearly the wreck we might have expected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine hugs Dr. Bennett and shakes hands with his WIFE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The service is crowded, more than 200 people, many more than expected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As his mother talks to a WELL-WISHER, Will looks left to see an Oldsmobile parking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON the license plates.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Missouri.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The passenger side opens, but the man who steps out is barely visible over the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shuts it to reveal himself to be 70.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Amos Calloway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will doesn't recognize him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Driver climbs out, a size 15 foot on the gravel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We TILT UP to see this man is huge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This man is KARL, now 55.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's not 12 feet tall, but at least six-eight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON Will, bewildered to see that this man really exists.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CEMETERY / GRAVESIDE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the service gets ready to begin, Will guides his mother to a seat near the grave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting beside Will, Josephine spots a stunning ASIAN WOMAN (50) behind them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat later, an identical face with glasses peers out -- the woman's twin sister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's PING and JING.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Josephine almost GASPS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She elbows Will, who turns to look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From this angle the sisters seem conjoined, but then Jing steps forward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're really two separate people.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A sea of familiar faces, all of them aged through the years: BEAMEN, NORTHER WINSLOW, the MAYOR, and ZACKY PRICE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CEMETERY - DAY [LATER]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After the service, we see the crowd gathered in small groups.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By the LAUGHTER and hand gestures, we can see they're telling stories.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're telling Edward's stories.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We find Will watching them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Have you ever heard a joke so many times you've forgotten why it's funny?
{DIALOGUE}: But then you hear it again and suddenly it's new.
{DIALOGUE}: You remember why you loved it in the first place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will joins in, laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We slowly CIRCLE BEHIND a monument, letting it black out the screen.
{META_DATA}: TRANSITION TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BLOOM HOUSE BACKYARD - DAY [SUMMER]
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will sits on the porch with Sandra and Josephine, watching his SON play in the pool with two NEIGHBOR KIDS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SON
{META_DATA}: (to the other boys)
{DIALOGUE}: So he said he'd fight the giant who was fifteen feet tall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KID
{DIALOGUE}: No way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SON
{META_DATA}: (calling over)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, that's right, isn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL
{DIALOGUE}: Something like that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SON
{DIALOGUE}: See.
{DIALOGUE}: So he was a giant but my grampa was going to fight him because he wasn't afraid of anything because he'd seen how he was going to die in this old lady's glass eye...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Will smiles as his son continues the tale, which FADES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sandra takes Will's hand in hers, just listening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: That was my father's final joke I guess.
{DIALOGUE}: A man tells his stories so many times he becomes the stories.
{DIALOGUE}: They live on after him.
{META_DATA}: CROSSFADE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RIVER / UNDERWATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fat and happy catfish swims towards us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And in that way, he becomes immortal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The fish passes us with a SPLASH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CUT TO BLACK.
{META_DATA}: THE END
